WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.540
[Amit Varma]: One of the things that makes us unique as a species is our language. Humans speak in

00:00:10.540 --> 00:00:15.920
[Amit Varma]: languages that can embody concepts, construct and contain narratives, communicate across

00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:22.040
[Amit Varma]: time and space. And yet, just as language unites us, it also divides us. There are over

00:00:22.040 --> 00:00:27.280
[Amit Varma]: 6,000 languages in existence, at least 1,000 of which have a written form. We live this

00:00:27.280 --> 00:00:32.320
[Amit Varma]: beautiful diversity every day on the streets of India. And there is great art created in

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:37.320
[Amit Varma]: all these languages, the best of which combines local flavor with a universal essence, which

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:42.800
[Amit Varma]: anyone from anywhere could relate to, if they could understand the language. This multiplicity

00:00:42.800 --> 00:00:48.440
[Amit Varma]: of languages is beautiful, but presents one problem. As readers, how can we understand

00:00:48.440 --> 00:00:54.320
[Amit Varma]: the wonders of other languages? We rely on translation. And that is why if language is

00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:59.520
[Amit Varma]: essential and writing is important, then translation matters.

