00:03:07.040 --> 00:03:13.560
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen. Thank you, Amit. Thank you for having me here. So

00:03:13.560 --> 00:03:18.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, before we sort of get to your fascinating career, I remember you, I remember your byline

00:03:18.720 --> 00:03:23.320
[Amit Varma]: from like a long, long time ago, mainly as a journalist. Then I gradually became aware

00:03:23.320 --> 00:03:27.080
[Amit Varma]: of your remarkable career and all these books. And I'm of course, half Bengali. And yeah,

00:03:27.080 --> 00:03:31.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, my father reads all your books and talks about you a lot. So I think he'll be

00:03:31.200 --> 00:03:35.240
[Amit Varma]: delighted that you're finally on my show. Tell me a little bit about yourself. Like,

00:03:35.240 --> 00:03:39.800
[Guest]: you know, where did you grow up? What was your education? Yeah, so I was born in Calcutta

00:03:39.800 --> 00:03:44.200
[Guest]: and I grew up there. Well, I technically spent the first four years of my life in Bombay,

00:03:44.200 --> 00:03:50.320
[Guest]: but very faint memories of that period. I went to school in Calcutta. And then like

00:03:50.320 --> 00:03:55.640
[Guest]: all or most Bengali boys of my generation, I was prepping for a, you know, you either

00:03:55.640 --> 00:04:00.440
[Guest]: go into medicine or you go into engineering. And I was prepping for engineering. I actually

00:04:00.440 --> 00:04:06.560
[Guest]: got in surprising even myself. I got into Jadavpur University and I joined electrical

00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:12.480
[Guest]: engineering. It took about three weeks to realise that this was not for me. And also

00:04:12.480 --> 00:04:16.760
[Guest]: that you know, there was no sense in wasting what could be the best or some of the best

00:04:16.760 --> 00:04:22.760
[Guest]: years of your life studying something that you didn't want to. So I contrived to fail

00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:27.400
[Guest]: enough papers and create and burn my boats as it was so that there was no looking back.

00:04:27.400 --> 00:04:32.840
[Guest]: I couldn't go back and start again. And I started afresh the next year with English

00:04:32.840 --> 00:04:38.920
[Guest]: literature in the same university on the same campus. So it was a complete turn as far as

00:04:38.920 --> 00:04:46.000
[Guest]: I imagine that my life took a completely different turn. While I was studying English literature,

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:51.280
[Guest]: the whole idea was then I was fairly set on being an academic. So you know, BA, MA, then

00:04:51.280 --> 00:04:56.920
[Guest]: you go for, back then you had to do an MFL and then you try to go abroad for a period.

00:04:56.920 --> 00:05:01.960
[Guest]: So that was the set path. But we used to bring out a college magazine, you know, in the old

00:05:01.960 --> 00:05:10.000
[Guest]: cyclostyle format. And immediately after my BA final exams, a job opportunity opened up

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:14.600
[Guest]: in a youth magazine in Calcutta, which I took. And six months or not even six months, within

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:17.960
[Guest]: three months of that, I was sure that that was what I wanted to do. So there went the

00:05:17.960 --> 00:05:22.740
[Guest]: academic track completely. I enrolled for my MA, didn't go through with it after the

00:05:22.740 --> 00:05:28.160
[Guest]: first year, and just became a journalist. And that too, a sort of entrepreneurial journalist

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:33.000
[Guest]: in the sense that it was our own magazine. After we managed to run that to the ground

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:38.360
[Guest]: in about two years, we started a city magazine, and that was funded by what you would today

00:05:38.360 --> 00:05:44.080
[Guest]: call an angel investor. And that did quite well. We actually had a circulation of about

00:05:44.080 --> 00:05:45.080
[Guest]: 20,000.

00:05:45.080 --> 00:05:46.080
[Guest]: Wow, that's crazy.

00:05:46.080 --> 00:05:50.840
[Guest]: And yeah, a monthly magazine. And we even pioneered this whole business of local listings,

00:05:50.840 --> 00:05:58.520
[Guest]: paid local listings, which became the rage much later. So it was good, but we couldn't

00:05:58.520 --> 00:06:03.760
[Guest]: manage the finances well enough. So four years later, the angel investor who had since then

00:06:03.760 --> 00:06:06.760
[Guest]: handed over to another one, they said, sorry, we were out of cash.

00:06:06.760 --> 00:06:07.760
[Guest]: What was this called?

00:06:07.760 --> 00:06:08.760
[Guest]: It was called Calcutta Skyline.

00:06:08.760 --> 00:06:09.760
[Guest]: Okay.

00:06:09.760 --> 00:06:14.440
[Guest]: But interestingly, it was also where the seeds of my future, which I had no idea about at

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:19.400
[Guest]: that stage as a translator, was sown because we used to translate one short story from

00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:23.360
[Guest]: Bengali every month for every issue. And I did several of those translations and also

00:06:23.360 --> 00:06:28.080
[Guest]: sort of spearheaded that whole initiative, roping in others to translate as well. So

00:06:28.080 --> 00:06:32.480
[Guest]: then I worked for a little bit longer in Calcutta and then moved to Delhi as, believe it or

00:06:32.480 --> 00:06:39.880
[Guest]: not, a business journalist, with having absolutely zero credentials, except writing. But I worked

00:06:39.880 --> 00:06:44.680
[Guest]: for Business Today for eight years, which became a management magazine in the 90s. So

00:06:44.680 --> 00:06:48.640
[Guest]: it was interesting because you didn't have to know the nuts and bolts of what normally

00:06:48.640 --> 00:06:53.640
[Guest]: went into a business magazine. And doing a management oriented magazine meant that you

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:59.660
[Guest]: had to read enormously and assimilate enormously and then write it in a way that would be both

00:06:59.660 --> 00:07:02.440
[Guest]: engaging and lucid.

00:07:02.440 --> 00:07:06.640
[Guest]: Then in 2000, you know, even then we were writing about the net a good deal because

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:11.200
[Guest]: technology was very much part of management. And then in 2000, when the internet media

00:07:11.200 --> 00:07:15.580
[Guest]: opened up in India, so I decided that I was going to move in there. So I sort of walked

00:07:15.580 --> 00:07:20.600
[Guest]: into the india.com offices. And I said, you know, this is where I'm going to work. And

00:07:20.600 --> 00:07:23.840
[Guest]: they said, Who the hell are you? So I said, it doesn't matter how many people do you have

00:07:23.840 --> 00:07:27.760
[Guest]: walking in to say that they want to work for you. So you know, just don't look gift houses

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:32.120
[Guest]: in the mouth. I've been a journalist and just take my word for it. So they did actually

00:07:32.120 --> 00:07:36.520
[Guest]: and I moved to Bangalore from Delhi. And so yeah, I'd moved to Delhi before that from

00:07:36.520 --> 00:07:41.320
[Guest]: Calcutta for Business Today and then on to Bangalore for two years. Then, as usual, with

00:07:41.320 --> 00:07:48.800
[Guest]: my Midas touch india.com folded. So then I moved back to Delhi with India Times. And

00:07:48.800 --> 00:07:55.200
[Guest]: then it was in the internet for a long time after that for about 12 years, being a journalist.

00:07:55.200 --> 00:08:00.800
[Guest]: And then I moved on to being a product manager, building new products, which I did for a startup

00:08:00.800 --> 00:08:08.240
[Guest]: called ibibo. And then for NDTV.com as well. So yeah, this is my, my life as a journalist.

00:08:08.240 --> 00:08:12.200
[Amit Varma]: Wow, that's quite an arc. And what kind of struck me when you were talking about your

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:17.160
[Amit Varma]: decision in college to fail your engineering exams was when you said that you decided immediately

00:08:17.160 --> 00:08:20.560
[Amit Varma]: that you don't want to waste the best years of your life. Yeah. And the thought that struck

00:08:20.560 --> 00:08:25.960
[Amit Varma]: me was that that is an enormous amount of maturity for a fresher undergrad. Because

00:08:25.960 --> 00:08:32.160
[Amit Varma]: I remember at that age, my thinking was not at all as clear about things. And and then

00:08:32.160 --> 00:08:35.680
[Amit Varma]: you said you went on to do English lit. So I'm guessing that a lot of this must have

00:08:35.680 --> 00:08:40.480
[Amit Varma]: been driven by a love for books. So what kind of books did you read? Did you read in both

00:08:40.480 --> 00:08:45.200
[Amit Varma]: English and Bengali? You know, what was the shaping of your literary taste?

00:08:45.200 --> 00:08:50.360
[Guest]: So I used to read exclusively in Bengali till the age of about eight. I started reading

00:08:50.360 --> 00:08:55.840
[Guest]: quite early. By about five, I was reading. And I was reading Bangla till eight when I

00:08:55.840 --> 00:09:01.040
[Guest]: discovered till seven, when I discovered Enid Blyton. And then I did this sort of overnight

00:09:01.040 --> 00:09:08.480
[Guest]: shift to reading English books. And so yeah, also school life, I think I devoured everything

00:09:08.480 --> 00:09:14.560
[Guest]: there was for our age group. So starting with Enid Blyton, and then there were other very

00:09:14.560 --> 00:09:18.600
[Guest]: interesting school series around that time, you know, there was a lovely one by Eleanor

00:09:18.600 --> 00:09:24.560
[Guest]: M. Brent Dyer called the Chalice School, which was quite exotic, because that school was

00:09:24.560 --> 00:09:29.640
[Guest]: not even located anywhere fixed, they would move around different European countries.

00:09:29.640 --> 00:09:35.080
[Guest]: And back then in the 1970s, European countries were just a concept. I mean, you know, we

00:09:35.080 --> 00:09:39.880
[Guest]: had no idea what it actually meant. But this school was in Switzerland today and in Germany

00:09:39.880 --> 00:09:44.960
[Guest]: tomorrow, and it was a girl's school. So there was this, you know, other sort of undercurrent

00:09:44.960 --> 00:09:49.280
[Guest]: of fascination also because of the fact that these were clearly teenage girls, although

00:09:49.280 --> 00:09:54.000
[Guest]: completely antiseptic. But, you know, there were two levels of attraction as it were,

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.360
[Guest]: as one grew older. So there was those and then there was some teenage science fiction,

00:09:58.360 --> 00:10:02.720
[Guest]: a series called Tom Swift, which I remember reading a lot of and then moving very quickly

00:10:02.720 --> 00:10:09.960
[Guest]: on to trash. So Alastair Maclean, which is not trash, really, and Desmond Bagley, and

00:10:09.960 --> 00:10:15.160
[Guest]: then anything on the shelves at home, and I read indiscriminately, like I think everybody

00:10:15.160 --> 00:10:18.280
[Guest]: who loves everybody. So you pick one book, and then you pick the next book, and you pick

00:10:18.280 --> 00:10:22.520
[Guest]: the next book. So with the result that I was reading Camus, The Outsider, followed by Harold

00:10:22.520 --> 00:10:28.480
[Guest]: Robbins, Carpetbagger, followed by The Old Man and the Sea, which I hated at that point.

00:10:28.480 --> 00:10:30.000
[Guest]: You still hate it?

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:36.120
[Guest]: Yeah, I'm ambivalent about Old Man. I'm ambivalent about, I mean, great writing, but too much

00:10:36.120 --> 00:10:42.920
[Guest]: machismo for me. And then Somerset Maugham, whom I really couldn't stand. I don't know.

00:10:42.920 --> 00:10:47.360
[Guest]: And unfortunately, I think some of these early impressions are very hard to undo. So even

00:10:47.360 --> 00:10:52.280
[Guest]: if it turns out later that no, no, no, these are good people to read, you are just somehow,

00:10:52.280 --> 00:10:56.560
[Guest]: you know, it's baked into you that I don't like Somerset Maugham and that's it. But yeah,

00:10:56.560 --> 00:11:00.200
[Guest]: and Woodhouse, I said, and Woodhouse, I think was the biggest value of reading Woodhouse

00:11:00.200 --> 00:11:04.680
[Guest]: was becoming sensitive about language. But Woodhouse, he almost read purely at the level

00:11:04.680 --> 00:11:05.680
[Amit Varma]: of language.

00:11:05.680 --> 00:11:06.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's the whole point.

00:11:06.680 --> 00:11:11.720
[Guest]: The incidents didn't matter at all. Right. So yeah, so quite a lot of reading. Bangla,

00:11:11.720 --> 00:11:16.840
[Guest]: I did not read too much at that point. But we had to study it in school. And then I found

00:11:16.840 --> 00:11:23.600
[Guest]: it very difficult to write. It was proving to be a very tall order. So my uncle, my father's

00:11:23.600 --> 00:11:29.080
[Guest]: elder cousin, who himself is a poet, he put me through my paces of writing by making me

00:11:29.080 --> 00:11:35.000
[Guest]: summarise the art textbooks. And that in some mysterious way got me into both reading and

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:40.240
[Guest]: writing Bangla again at a more mature level. My spelling, my Bangla spelling became almost

00:11:40.240 --> 00:11:46.160
[Guest]: perfect, which is unbelievable. But I realised that by the act of writing fixes your spelling.

00:11:46.160 --> 00:11:50.880
[Guest]: Then I started reading a good deal in Bangla as well, starting, mind you, with trash. I

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:56.080
[Guest]: still remember this one particular book, which was called Hutta Himel Hawa, which literally

00:11:56.080 --> 00:12:03.000
[Guest]: is, you know, murder cold wind. And there was this very clear extramarital affair that

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:09.800
[Guest]: was going on between the wife of an industrialist and her sarod instructor. And it was full

00:12:09.800 --> 00:12:16.000
[Guest]: of these very elegant ways of describing physical relationships, you know, so much so that for

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:21.800
[Guest]: the longest time, I always used to think that a kiss could only be described as imprinting

00:12:21.800 --> 00:12:27.040
[Guest]: the mark of your lips on another's. I mean, I did not know any other way of putting it.

00:12:27.040 --> 00:12:32.280
[Guest]: So yeah. But yeah, I read, I read a lot in both languages. That is true.

00:12:32.280 --> 00:12:36.480
[Amit Varma]: No, and this is making me really nostalgic. Because obviously, you know, there are certain

00:12:36.480 --> 00:12:41.760
[Amit Varma]: authors and certain sort of canons, which are very familiar to Indians growing up in

00:12:41.760 --> 00:12:46.080
[Unknown]: the 70s, 80s, 90s. I don't think Somerset Maugham would have been read so much outside

00:12:46.080 --> 00:12:51.680
[Amit Varma]: the country necessarily in the West. But over here, and also the sort of the deification

00:12:51.680 --> 00:12:57.880
[Amit Varma]: of Woodhouse and the pedestal that he is quite correctly put on, is sort of strikes a chord.

00:12:57.880 --> 00:12:59.480
[Amit Varma]: Did you also want to be a writer?

00:12:59.480 --> 00:13:02.080
[Guest]: No, I never actually wanted to be a writer.

00:13:02.080 --> 00:13:04.280
[Amit Varma]: Even though you were a journalist, and you did write a lot?

00:13:04.280 --> 00:13:09.120
[Guest]: Yeah, even so. I mean, yeah, I've never wanted to be to write and I'm full of admiration

00:13:09.120 --> 00:13:14.680
[Guest]: for people who can write books. And I don't think I'm capable of actually finishing writing

00:13:14.680 --> 00:13:15.680
[Guest]: a complete book.

00:13:15.680 --> 00:13:20.120
[Amit Varma]: Well, that's very interesting. So, you know, so you you had translated these couple of

00:13:20.120 --> 00:13:24.600
[Amit Varma]: stories for the magazine when you were young. And then you come back to translation more

00:13:24.600 --> 00:13:25.600
[Guest]: than a decade and a half later.

00:13:25.600 --> 00:13:28.960
[Guest]: So what happened was that just before I, so the story is that just before I left Calcutta,

00:13:28.960 --> 00:13:35.560
[Guest]: this was in 1992. Shankod, who some of whose stories I had translated for the magazine,

00:13:35.560 --> 00:13:39.920
[Guest]: actually, he got in touch with me, and he said that he wanted an English translation

00:13:39.920 --> 00:13:45.480
[Guest]: of Chaurangi. And he said that it was for a French publisher who wanted to read an English

00:13:45.480 --> 00:13:50.920
[Guest]: version before taking the decision to translate it into French. And back then, mind you, 92.

00:13:50.920 --> 00:13:56.660
[Guest]: So I don't think English language publishing in the new wave had started yet. Penguin may

00:13:56.660 --> 00:14:01.400
[Guest]: have just set up with Anando. No, they had, I think, by the late 80s, they were already

00:14:01.400 --> 00:14:06.840
[Guest]: publishing Sunil Ganguly and others, I think. But yeah, they were the only ones. And there

00:14:06.840 --> 00:14:10.920
[Guest]: was no sense that, you know, you could actually translate for being published, the concept

00:14:10.920 --> 00:14:15.200
[Guest]: didn't exist. So I translated it for him in a few years, I did it in about a month and

00:14:15.200 --> 00:14:19.800
[Guest]: a half, you know, staying back in the office late at night after work and bashing it out

00:14:19.800 --> 00:14:25.400
[Guest]: on the office computer, and then taking printouts on those old accordion folded, you know, dot

00:14:25.400 --> 00:14:30.520
[Guest]: matrix printers on those accordion folded pages. And then before leaving Delhi, leaving

00:14:30.520 --> 00:14:35.240
[Guest]: Calcutta for Delhi, I handed him the whole potha, as it was, here's your novel in English.

00:14:35.240 --> 00:14:37.320
[Amit Varma]: Was it the only copy that you handed?

00:14:37.320 --> 00:14:43.680
[Guest]: It was the only copy. It was the only copy. And I gave it to him. No, but I kept a copy

00:14:43.680 --> 00:14:48.320
[Guest]: on a five and a half inch floppy disk, which was the disk drive back then. A word star

00:14:48.320 --> 00:14:49.320
[Guest]: document.

00:14:49.320 --> 00:14:52.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I remember those thin brown thingies.

00:14:52.240 --> 00:14:56.720
[Guest]: Yeah. And I carried that with me under the impression that five and a half inch floppies

00:14:56.720 --> 00:15:01.600
[Guest]: were going to live forever, and so on. And then I had a digital copy. So what me worry.

00:15:01.600 --> 00:15:06.140
[Guest]: And then there was no word from him and nothing. Occasionally, you know, when I was when you

00:15:06.140 --> 00:15:10.760
[Guest]: had this spiritual crisis at work, I would toy with the idea of let me translate a novel.

00:15:10.760 --> 00:15:17.800
[Guest]: But of course, I never got beyond a line or two. Cut to 2006. Now 2006, I am already at

00:15:17.800 --> 00:15:22.800
[Guest]: that age where I'm about to have a full blown midlife crisis. So red Ferrari or something

00:15:22.800 --> 00:15:27.040
[Guest]: equally weird is going to happen. I know it. I know that it hit me in the face at that

00:15:27.040 --> 00:15:33.520
[Guest]: point. When I get a call from Diya Kaur at Penguin, whom I because all Calcutta people,

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:39.480
[Guest]: you know, know one another. It's a village. So she called and she said, did you ever translate

00:15:39.480 --> 00:15:43.400
[Guest]: Chaurangi? And I said, wow, this is a true blast from the past world. How did this come

00:15:43.400 --> 00:15:47.360
[Guest]: to you? So she said, you know, we want to publish a translation and we got in touch

00:15:47.360 --> 00:15:50.840
[Guest]: with the writer and Shankar said, look, there is a translation, but I don't remember who

00:15:50.840 --> 00:15:57.760
[Guest]: did it, but I have the printout. So he sent it to us and I found your name on it. So luckily

00:15:57.760 --> 00:15:59.960
[Amit Varma]: I put my name on the on the copy.

00:15:59.960 --> 00:16:02.800
[Amit Varma]: Smart move. I think your floppy disk by now would have disappeared.

00:16:02.800 --> 00:16:06.480
[Guest]: Yeah, so there's a story behind that as well. So and she said, so we'd love to publish it.

00:16:06.480 --> 00:16:09.840
[Guest]: So I said, oh, that's fantastic. And what do I have to do? So she said, do you want

00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:13.960
[Guest]: to take another look at the text? I said, okay, sure. And then I said, I don't need

00:16:13.960 --> 00:16:18.840
[Guest]: a printout. I have my floppy disk. So I took my floppy disk, which had strangely enough,

00:16:18.840 --> 00:16:23.800
[Guest]: survived several house moves and city moves and so on. So I took it to Nehru Place and

00:16:23.800 --> 00:16:29.000
[Guest]: I said, can you get the data out of this one? But after two days, even they threw their

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:34.360
[Guest]: hand up and said, no, we are not able to. So I took that printout and I gave it to a

00:16:34.360 --> 00:16:37.880
[Guest]: professional typist. And I said, now you type it all out for me, because by that time, of

00:16:37.880 --> 00:16:42.080
[Guest]: course, we moved to a different platform. We've got Microsoft Word. So he typed it all

00:16:42.080 --> 00:16:48.880
[Guest]: out for me. And then I lightly edited it a bit. And then that was it. They published

00:16:48.880 --> 00:16:55.680
[Guest]: it. That was very unexpected. And was it successful? It was extreme. It's probably been my most

00:16:55.680 --> 00:17:00.360
[Guest]: successful book, in the sense of sales in India. Yeah, it was extremely successful.

00:17:00.360 --> 00:17:07.560
[Guest]: And funnily or not, I signed away the copyright and all monetary considerations at the time

00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:12.060
[Guest]: I translated it for the princely sum, actually not princely, it was quite a decent amount

00:17:12.060 --> 00:17:16.640
[Guest]: back then of 6,000 rupees, which was twice my monthly salary in the late 80s, in the

00:17:16.640 --> 00:17:17.640
[Guest]: in 92.

00:17:17.640 --> 00:17:18.640
[Amit Varma]: That's not bad.

00:17:18.640 --> 00:17:23.600
[Guest]: That was 2x of my monthly salary, I used to earn 3,000 rupees a month. So I was very pleased

00:17:23.600 --> 00:17:28.120
[Guest]: 6,000 rupees just as I'm moving cities was a windfall to me. But and I had no idea how

00:17:28.120 --> 00:17:32.800
[Guest]: publishing worked, how copyrights worked and so on. So eventually turned out that I made

00:17:32.800 --> 00:17:38.800
[Guest]: absolutely no money from the sales and from the sales abroad. But, you know, it started

00:17:38.800 --> 00:17:42.080
[Guest]: me off on something on what's become my life. So I have...

00:17:42.080 --> 00:17:45.680
[Amit Varma]: But is it fair to say that you do what you do because of the love of it, the money is

00:17:45.680 --> 00:17:49.040
[Amit Varma]: a nice bonus. But it's the work is its own reward.

00:17:49.040 --> 00:17:53.840
[Guest]: Yeah, the money is a nice bonus. And it helps holidays and other expenses. You can't build

00:17:53.840 --> 00:17:58.640
[Guest]: your life around your earnings from translations. So yeah, it's not primarily the money, but

00:17:58.640 --> 00:18:03.440
[Guest]: it isn't for I mean, I've met many translators around the world. And even the ones who earn

00:18:03.440 --> 00:18:06.160
[Guest]: well, don't do it for the money, or primarily for the money.

00:18:06.160 --> 00:18:10.880
[Amit Varma]: I was reading Edith Grossman's book, Why Translation Matters. And there's a quote from it, which

00:18:10.880 --> 00:18:17.160
[Amit Varma]: struck me. And she writes, quote, translation is a strange craft, generally appreciated

00:18:17.160 --> 00:18:21.200
[Amit Varma]: by writers, with a few glaring exceptions, like Milan Kundera, whose attack on his French

00:18:21.200 --> 00:18:26.440
[Amit Varma]: translator was so virulent, it achieved a kind of a sour kind of notoriety. Undervalued

00:18:26.440 --> 00:18:31.560
[Amit Varma]: by publishers, translators fees tend to be so low that agents generally are not interested

00:18:31.560 --> 00:18:36.880
[Amit Varma]: in representing them. Trivialized by the academic world, there are still promotion and tenure

00:18:36.880 --> 00:18:41.560
[Amit Varma]: committees that do not consider translations to be serious publications, and practically

00:18:41.560 --> 00:18:46.440
[Amit Varma]: ignored by reviewers. Astonishingly, it is still possible to find reviews that do not

00:18:46.440 --> 00:18:51.160
[Amit Varma]: even mention the translator's name, let alone discuss the quality of the translation. It

00:18:51.160 --> 00:18:57.120
[Amit Varma]: is an occupation that many critics agree is impossible at best, a betrayal at worst, and

00:18:57.120 --> 00:19:02.560
[Amit Varma]: on the average, probably not much more than the accumulated result of a diligent, even

00:19:02.560 --> 00:19:07.760
[Amit Varma]: slavish familiarity with dictionaries, although bringing a text over into another language

00:19:07.760 --> 00:19:13.440
[Amit Varma]: has a long and glorious history. Stop quote. So this brings me to the question, why on

00:19:13.440 --> 00:19:14.440
[Amit Varma]: earth did you become a translator?

00:19:14.440 --> 00:19:19.440
[Guest]: Yeah, so you know, it's a great question, because I don't know. And again, I've asked

00:19:19.440 --> 00:19:24.720
[Guest]: others how, why and how, and all of them have the same answer. We don't know. There's some

00:19:24.720 --> 00:19:28.960
[Guest]: button somewhere, you know, that makes you I think it's the instinct of amateur singer

00:19:28.960 --> 00:19:35.080
[Guest]: who's quite good as a singer, but will never make it as a top class singer. So what do

00:19:35.080 --> 00:19:39.520
[Guest]: you do when you hear anything, you start humming it, right? And you want to sing it to perfection,

00:19:39.520 --> 00:19:43.480
[Guest]: because you want to recreate that same feeling that you had when you heard the original.

00:19:43.480 --> 00:19:47.680
[Guest]: I think it's an instinct like that. So that's what makes you do it. But I can tell you this,

00:19:47.680 --> 00:19:53.440
[Guest]: it's a drug. You start and you cannot stop. You really cannot stop you. I mean, I'm at

00:19:53.440 --> 00:19:59.000
[Guest]: the point where if I finish like the, like Trollop. So like Trollop, I think it was Trollop,

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:04.040
[Guest]: if I finish a translation at 6.15 in the evening, I will start a new one at 6.25. I kid you

00:20:04.040 --> 00:20:09.720
[Guest]: not. It is really like that. And because finishing a translation is such a feeling of the end

00:20:09.720 --> 00:20:14.640
[Guest]: of the world that the only way you can survive is by starting the next one. So it is a drug.

00:20:14.640 --> 00:20:18.800
[Guest]: And I think there's a certain amount of ego involved. Because you know, you feel, although

00:20:18.800 --> 00:20:22.480
[Guest]: anyone not too many people might know that, hey, so many thousands of people would not

00:20:22.480 --> 00:20:26.760
[Guest]: have read this book had I not translated it. And if you come to think of it, if translators

00:20:26.760 --> 00:20:32.120
[Guest]: go on strike around the world, world literature is going to collapse. Publishing is going

00:20:32.120 --> 00:20:38.600
[Guest]: to collapse. So it's incredible that something that is so important a part of the literary

00:20:38.600 --> 00:20:45.480
[Guest]: system is actually not acknowledged for I think what it achieves, or the people behind

00:20:45.480 --> 00:20:50.120
[Guest]: it are not acknowledged to the extent perhaps that they should. But having said that, I

00:20:50.120 --> 00:20:54.000
[Guest]: don't think that that's a problem. Because you know, at the end of the day, there are

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:59.160
[Guest]: exceptions, I'm sure. But most translators don't do it for to be considered important

00:20:59.160 --> 00:21:05.000
[Amit Varma]: people. And also, I would guess that when you translate something, you are of course,

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:07.920
[Amit Varma]: one you're driven by the book that you're translating is something that you love, and

00:21:07.920 --> 00:21:13.040
[Amit Varma]: you want to share it with everyone, but also by the creative urge. Because, you know, typically,

00:21:13.040 --> 00:21:16.960
[Amit Varma]: the non reader would assume that translation is nothing than you know, you can take a dictionary

00:21:16.960 --> 00:21:22.760
[Amit Varma]: and one day AI will do it and you just transcribe all the words, but it's actually not that

00:21:22.760 --> 00:21:28.280
[Amit Varma]: and I'm reminded of, you know, Gregory Rabassa, who was Marquez's famous translator, while

00:21:28.280 --> 00:21:32.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, after he translated the book was asked this bizarre question by this interviewer

00:21:32.920 --> 00:21:37.280
[Amit Varma]: on do you know enough Spanish to be able to translate the work and Rabassa's incredible

00:21:37.280 --> 00:21:41.640
[Amit Varma]: response was that the question is not whether I know enough Spanish, the question is whether

00:21:41.640 --> 00:21:47.080
[Amit Varma]: I know enough English, you know, thereby indicating that, you know, it's almost like creating

00:21:47.080 --> 00:21:52.160
[Amit Varma]: an entirely new work, you know, another famous translator, Herbert Bates, who translated

00:21:52.160 --> 00:21:57.160
[Amit Varma]: Odyssey earlier, of course, which is, you know, Emily Wilson's latest translation is

00:21:57.160 --> 00:22:01.600
[Amit Varma]: quite mind blowing. But Bates said once said about translation, and this is a very sexist

00:22:01.600 --> 00:22:07.160
[Amit Varma]: remark, but it was made many, many decades earlier, where he said that a translation

00:22:07.160 --> 00:22:12.280
[Amit Varma]: can be like a wife, if she's beautiful, she won't be faithful. If she's faithful, she

00:22:12.280 --> 00:22:16.880
[Amit Varma]: won't be beautiful, which is incredibly sexist, but there is something to that also. So is

00:22:16.880 --> 00:22:21.000
[Amit Varma]: this a trade off that you encounter while translating that, you know, on the one hand,

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:25.760
[Amit Varma]: you want to get everything right, and you know, not change too much. But on the other

00:22:25.760 --> 00:22:30.440
[Amit Varma]: hand, your true field to your true loyalty is to the essence of what is what the author

00:22:30.440 --> 00:22:34.800
[Amit Varma]: is trying to convey. So how has your response to this evolved? Like, was this something

00:22:34.800 --> 00:22:38.920
[Amit Varma]: that you thought about consciously reading up what others said on it, especially while

00:22:38.920 --> 00:22:43.240
[Amit Varma]: doing your first translation? Or did you sort of discover your own thinking on it as you

00:22:43.240 --> 00:22:44.240
[Guest]: went along?

00:22:44.240 --> 00:22:47.960
[Guest]: Yeah, it's the latter. When I did my first translation, I had no idea of what thoughts

00:22:47.960 --> 00:22:51.840
[Guest]: had gone into the process, especially because remember, those days, these books were not

00:22:51.840 --> 00:22:55.840
[Guest]: available the way they are now and there was no internet. So there was no way really of

00:22:55.840 --> 00:22:59.600
[Guest]: reading up. And if at all you went to the library and read, you only read things like

00:22:59.600 --> 00:23:03.980
[Guest]: Walter Benjamin's famous essay and so on, which was delightful, but completely useless

00:23:03.980 --> 00:23:09.680
[Guest]: when it came to actually translating into a translation strategy. So yeah, my first

00:23:09.680 --> 00:23:13.640
[Guest]: and I realized when I look back now at my earlier work that I was very much focused

00:23:13.640 --> 00:23:20.080
[Guest]: on bringing the words over into the new language. And very often that led to certain angularities.

00:23:20.080 --> 00:23:26.240
[Guest]: One of a British critic described my translation of Chaurangi as fruity and spicy. And I think

00:23:26.240 --> 00:23:31.840
[Guest]: it was a very kind way of saying that it was not English. It had all these, you know, exotic

00:23:31.840 --> 00:23:37.760
[Guest]: equatorial flavours as it were from a different land. But in retrospect, I wonder if that's

00:23:37.760 --> 00:23:43.720
[Guest]: necessarily a bad thing either. So, you know, the real battle is not about fealty and beauty

00:23:43.720 --> 00:23:48.800
[Guest]: because there's no conflict between them. The real battle, which you're always fighting

00:23:48.800 --> 00:23:53.760
[Guest]: and negotiating in your head is, let's say I'm translating from Bangla, well, let's say

00:23:53.760 --> 00:24:01.360
[Guest]: I am translating from Bangla to English. So is my English going to bring Bangla into it?

00:24:01.360 --> 00:24:07.280
[Guest]: Or is the Bangla text going to become an English text? That is the real battle, you know. So

00:24:07.280 --> 00:24:12.120
[Guest]: the point is that, you know, after translation, will it then slip so easily into the stream

00:24:12.120 --> 00:24:18.480
[Guest]: of English or literature written in the English language that you no longer think of its origins?

00:24:18.480 --> 00:24:22.920
[Guest]: It now belongs to all the books that have been written in English. And that's a perfectly

00:24:22.920 --> 00:24:29.760
[Guest]: fine strategy to go with. If in the process of doing that, you may have to do, you know,

00:24:29.760 --> 00:24:34.240
[Guest]: adopt certain tactics where you are saying that I will not make the reader stumble on

00:24:34.240 --> 00:24:37.920
[Guest]: anything when they're reading it in English because, hey, the reader did not stumble on

00:24:37.920 --> 00:24:45.920
[Guest]: the original. So my attempt is to be faithful to the experience of the reader and the experience

00:24:45.920 --> 00:24:51.040
[Guest]: of the reader in terms of the ease with which he can, he or she, they can navigate the text.

00:24:51.040 --> 00:24:55.880
[Guest]: For example, if I am reading the original text with a sense of, I understand this, I

00:24:55.880 --> 00:25:00.480
[Guest]: get this, should I make the reader interrogate the text when it goes into a new language

00:25:00.480 --> 00:25:06.000
[Guest]: because I am insistent on keeping some of the flavours and material and words from the

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:10.880
[Guest]: original language? Or I can say that, no, it's not an English text. It is a text which

00:25:10.880 --> 00:25:17.280
[Guest]: has been rendered into English, but it belongs to another language. And therefore, I don't

00:25:17.280 --> 00:25:21.680
[Guest]: want you to read it as though it is part of the English canon. It is not. Remember always

00:25:21.680 --> 00:25:25.840
[Guest]: that it is a Bangla text or a text in a language that you are not familiar with. Therefore,

00:25:25.840 --> 00:25:30.040
[Guest]: you will encounter unfamiliarities the way you might not if you were reading a text written

00:25:30.040 --> 00:25:35.240
[Guest]: in English. And that is correct. That is the right approach because the reader of the Bangla

00:25:35.240 --> 00:25:38.860
[Guest]: text is not the reader of the English text. So why should I assume that two readers so

00:25:38.860 --> 00:25:45.400
[Guest]: far separated in space and time should have exactly the same kind of response or that

00:25:45.400 --> 00:25:50.560
[Guest]: the effect should be the same on both of you? And there is no one answer to this question.

00:25:50.560 --> 00:25:54.800
[Guest]: You know, it's a question that we bat around in our heads. And it's a question that I encounter

00:25:54.800 --> 00:26:01.160
[Guest]: continuously in the translation classes that I teach at Ashoka University. And I just eventually

00:26:01.160 --> 00:26:05.520
[Guest]: tell everybody that you have to come to your own conclusion. Neither answer is right or

00:26:05.520 --> 00:26:10.760
[Guest]: wrong. That is why you can have multiple translations of the same text and each may have a different

00:26:10.760 --> 00:26:16.320
[Guest]: objective. Gayatri Chakraborty Spivak's translations of Mahasaya Dadevi, for example, is faithful

00:26:16.320 --> 00:26:22.840
[Guest]: to all the academic aspects of the original text, which she wants to identify and then

00:26:22.840 --> 00:26:27.320
[Guest]: carry across to the reader. So these academic aspects of the original text are not necessarily

00:26:27.320 --> 00:26:31.600
[Guest]: what Mahasaya Dadevi intended when she was writing. But for an academic reader, for a

00:26:31.600 --> 00:26:35.960
[Guest]: reader who's reading it with a particular objective, they're crucial. And if you can

00:26:35.960 --> 00:26:41.280
[Guest]: get those aspects that you will respond to academically, cerebrally from the original

00:26:41.280 --> 00:26:45.960
[Guest]: text, then you must do the same thing from the English text. Absolutely right. Her motive

00:26:45.960 --> 00:26:51.160
[Guest]: is clearly enunciated in the extended introduction that she writes. So you know where she's coming

00:26:51.160 --> 00:26:56.040
[Guest]: from. Someone else might say, no, I just want to read it for, translate it for someone who

00:26:56.040 --> 00:27:00.720
[Guest]: is casually picking up a copy of the book and just wants to read it and is not interested

00:27:00.720 --> 00:27:04.520
[Guest]: in the academic ramifications. So that'll lead to a different kind of translation. And

00:27:04.520 --> 00:27:08.600
[Guest]: I'm not saying that these translations will be terrifically divergent from one another.

00:27:08.600 --> 00:27:14.260
[Guest]: Not at all. I mean, I've often picked up, for example, Lydia Davis has translated Proust.

00:27:14.260 --> 00:27:20.800
[Guest]: She's translated Swan's Way and she's called it the Way of Swan. And she says that my attempt

00:27:20.800 --> 00:27:25.480
[Guest]: is not to make the French English, but to make sure that the reader understands that

00:27:25.480 --> 00:27:30.040
[Guest]: there's a different language underneath, even if the words are English. To be honest, when

00:27:30.040 --> 00:27:34.400
[Guest]: I read the two translations, I can see the difference, but they're not so far apart for

00:27:34.400 --> 00:27:41.520
[Guest]: me that makes me think, oh, wow, this one is Anglicised and this one is not. But then

00:27:41.520 --> 00:27:47.240
[Guest]: you realise that it lies in some details here and there. So the divergences are not enormous,

00:27:47.240 --> 00:27:52.480
[Guest]: but in the translator's head, somewhere the strategies are different. So it's, as I said,

00:27:52.480 --> 00:27:57.200
[Guest]: it's not about beauty. I mean, the translation has to be as beautiful as the original. That

00:27:57.200 --> 00:28:00.960
[Guest]: goes without saying. And indeed, making it as beautiful as the original is part of the

00:28:00.960 --> 00:28:06.680
[Guest]: process of being faithful. You can't change the pulchritude quotient, so to speak, and

00:28:06.680 --> 00:28:11.000
[Guest]: still claim that you're true to the original, just because you're trying to maybe take across

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:15.840
[Guest]: the meanings of the words and the meanings of the words in a very limited sense. Because

00:28:15.840 --> 00:28:20.160
[Guest]: what is a word? What is a sentence? It is not just its dictionary equivalent. It is

00:28:20.160 --> 00:28:26.240
[Guest]: a rhythm, it is a sound, it is music, it is silence. What is the writer not saying in

00:28:26.240 --> 00:28:30.960
[Guest]: the sentence? You must make sure you don't give voice to what the writer has not given

00:28:30.960 --> 00:28:36.240
[Guest]: voice to. You must hear the silence and protect the silence. So it's a whole bunch of things.

00:28:36.240 --> 00:28:41.880
[Guest]: And really what you are faithful to as a translator is your reading of that text. Translator is

00:28:41.880 --> 00:28:47.600
[Guest]: the closest reader there can be of any text. I think even closer than the writer themselves.

00:28:47.600 --> 00:28:51.200
[Unknown]: So a couple of thoughts that sort of emerged from what you just said. One is when you're

00:28:51.200 --> 00:28:55.840
[Amit Varma]: talking about Gayatri Chakravorty Spivak's translation of Mahashweta Devi and her being

00:28:55.840 --> 00:29:00.480
[Amit Varma]: faithful to what she felt was the academic aspects of it, even though you said Mahashweta

00:29:00.480 --> 00:29:06.200
[Amit Varma]: Devi may not have intended those aspects. So now this brings up the question of, should

00:29:06.200 --> 00:29:11.760
[Amit Varma]: we think of the text as something that stands apart from the author and the author's possible

00:29:11.760 --> 00:29:16.640
[Amit Varma]: intention? For example, Ralph Mannheim said something which was quite interesting to me

00:29:16.640 --> 00:29:22.000
[Amit Varma]: where he said, quote, translators are like actors who speak the lines as the author would

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:28.340
[Amit Varma]: if the author could speak English, stop quote. So, you know, so when you're translating,

00:29:28.340 --> 00:29:32.720
[Amit Varma]: is that something at the back of your mind that what is the author's voice? How closely

00:29:32.720 --> 00:29:37.400
[Amit Varma]: can you replicate that in a separate language? How closely can you replicate the intention?

00:29:37.400 --> 00:29:41.480
[Amit Varma]: Or are you saying that this is the work, this is what the work means to me, and that's what

00:29:41.480 --> 00:29:44.440
[Amit Varma]: I have to get across and keep the author out of the equation?

00:29:44.440 --> 00:29:48.840
[Guest]: No, no, sorry. I think I didn't put that well. I don't mean at all that I am trying to take

00:29:48.840 --> 00:29:52.440
[Guest]: across what the work means to me, leaving the author out of the equation, not at all.

00:29:52.440 --> 00:29:57.080
[Guest]: And in fact, I don't believe that the translator should be interpreting the work in any way.

00:29:57.080 --> 00:30:02.480
[Guest]: But what I'm getting at is that the translator still reads it and, you know, hears the text

00:30:02.480 --> 00:30:07.720
[Guest]: and hears the voice. Now, the point is, I will be true to the voice that I'm hearing.

00:30:07.720 --> 00:30:11.600
[Guest]: Is that the voice that the author intended? I do not know. There is actually no way of

00:30:11.600 --> 00:30:18.080
[Guest]: knowing, right? But yeah, to the extent that I am intent on taking across the author's

00:30:18.080 --> 00:30:22.440
[Guest]: voice the way I hear it, it is very much the author's work that I'm taking across. But

00:30:22.440 --> 00:30:26.840
[Guest]: the interesting thing is that none of this is a deconstructed process. It's not as though

00:30:26.840 --> 00:30:32.160
[Guest]: you have to break it down into components, okay, voice, sound, rhythm, none of that.

00:30:32.160 --> 00:30:37.640
[Guest]: It's all fused in the text. And really, if you are led by the text, and if you're a good

00:30:37.640 --> 00:30:42.280
[Guest]: translator, then all of these things will automatically be carried through. So you don't

00:30:42.280 --> 00:30:47.600
[Guest]: have to worry about these things individually. When translating, you have to worry about

00:30:47.600 --> 00:30:51.520
[Guest]: whether after you've translated, whether when you're reading it, you're getting the same

00:30:51.520 --> 00:30:55.720
[Guest]: kind of feeling as when you read the original. That's important. You know, it's important

00:30:55.720 --> 00:31:00.560
[Guest]: to read it to yourself, read it out loud, go back to your memory of the original text

00:31:00.560 --> 00:31:04.680
[Guest]: and see if you're getting the same notion. If you're being carried along the same way,

00:31:04.680 --> 00:31:07.960
[Guest]: if you stop pausing at the right place, if you're laughing at the same spot, if you're

00:31:07.960 --> 00:31:14.040
[Guest]: crying at the same spots or not, these are important. So there's business of the effect

00:31:14.040 --> 00:31:18.480
[Guest]: you're trying to create in the reader. Now, some language, for example, English is not

00:31:18.480 --> 00:31:23.960
[Guest]: as effervescent a language as Bangla. Bangla can pile on metaphors one after the other,

00:31:23.960 --> 00:31:29.960
[Guest]: and it does not even seem very weird. Try translating Tagore literally into English

00:31:29.960 --> 00:31:35.800
[Guest]: and it will seem the most over-the-top text ever. As you can see when you read his own

00:31:35.800 --> 00:31:40.920
[Guest]: translations, they're weird, right? I mean, no wonder he attracted labels of being a mystic

00:31:40.920 --> 00:31:45.040
[Guest]: and so on. The original texts are anything but mystical. But once taken into English

00:31:45.040 --> 00:31:50.840
[Guest]: because of the strange images that are created, which are not, you know, they don't flow naturally

00:31:50.840 --> 00:31:55.440
[Guest]: from the English language, you end up with a very different notion of the text, even

00:31:55.440 --> 00:32:00.480
[Guest]: if the words are the same. So that is where, you know, your judgment has to come in. So

00:32:00.480 --> 00:32:04.120
[Guest]: you have to actually, when you're putting it into English, you have to actually temper

00:32:04.120 --> 00:32:10.360
[Guest]: it down because you want ultimately to achieve a similar effect. You know, Deborah Smith,

00:32:10.360 --> 00:32:16.720
[Guest]: who translated The Vegetarian from Korean, she was, there was a huge storm of criticism

00:32:16.720 --> 00:32:21.680
[Guest]: of her work from Korea when they said that, oh, there are many, she's completely changed

00:32:21.680 --> 00:32:27.480
[Guest]: the tone because Korean is a much, you know, it's like many languages from Asia. It operates

00:32:27.480 --> 00:32:32.680
[Guest]: at a much more metaphorical level. It is a higher pitch and so on. And English, she's

00:32:32.680 --> 00:32:37.960
[Guest]: sort of tamped it down. My point is that if you try to, you know, maintain that same pitch

00:32:37.960 --> 00:32:42.480
[Guest]: in English, it would be hysterical. So you actually do have to tamp it down. So these

00:32:42.480 --> 00:32:46.840
[Guest]: are the points where, you know, it's like the author is speaking out in the street and

00:32:46.840 --> 00:32:51.800
[Guest]: you hear him in the backdrop of all the other noises. And then suddenly, you know, you're

00:32:51.800 --> 00:32:56.120
[Guest]: translating him and you're putting him in a soundproof studio. You have to lower his

00:32:56.120 --> 00:33:00.320
[Amit Varma]: volume. Otherwise, he's going to sound abnormally loud. This is always actually seen, you know,

00:33:00.320 --> 00:33:05.320
[Amit Varma]: one of the things I wonder about that languages are so fundamentally different that are they

00:33:05.320 --> 00:33:09.880
[Amit Varma]: translatable at all? For example, I was reading this excellent book by Guy Deutscher called

00:33:09.880 --> 00:33:13.920
[Amit Varma]: Through the Language Glass. And there was a paragraph that struck me in that, quote,

00:33:13.920 --> 00:33:18.520
[Amit Varma]: there are four tongues worthy of the world's use, says the Talmud, Greek for song, Latin

00:33:18.520 --> 00:33:24.320
[Amit Varma]: for war, Syriac for lamentation, and Hebrew for ordinary speech. And later he writes,

00:33:24.320 --> 00:33:29.000
[Amit Varma]: the Holy Roman Emperor Charles V, King of Spain, Archduke of Austria, and master of

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:34.280
[Amit Varma]: several European tongues, profess to speaking, and now quote within the quote, Spanish to

00:33:34.280 --> 00:33:40.040
[Amit Varma]: God, Italian to women, French to men, and German to my horse, stop quote twice. And,

00:33:40.040 --> 00:33:46.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, it's, it's always struck me that, for example, my specific bias, my specific

00:33:46.160 --> 00:33:50.160
[Amit Varma]: taste in literature is towards minimal spare prose, which is why, you know, I like someone

00:33:50.160 --> 00:33:54.960
[Amit Varma]: like Hemingway, but which is also why I like a lot of Japanese fiction. And one reason

00:33:54.960 --> 00:33:59.840
[Amit Varma]: that I have speculated on why this might be so is that Japanese is just a more minimal

00:33:59.840 --> 00:34:04.600
[Amit Varma]: languages, less flowery, it's less whatever, even more so than English in a sense. And

00:34:04.600 --> 00:34:09.080
[Amit Varma]: equally languages like Urdu and Bengali are almost Baroque languages. There is so much

00:34:09.080 --> 00:34:14.200
[Amit Varma]: expression. And like you said that if you were to translate something literally, from

00:34:14.200 --> 00:34:20.520
[Amit Varma]: either Urdu or Bangla to English, it would just seem overblown, you know, the finest

00:34:20.520 --> 00:34:25.080
[Amit Varma]: Tagore poem beautifully translated, and I've tried it myself. And if you just stay faithful

00:34:25.080 --> 00:34:29.400
[Amit Varma]: to each of the words, and you translate them, it just sounds bad because of the aesthetic

00:34:29.400 --> 00:34:34.200
[Amit Varma]: values inherent in the English language are very different. Exactly. So how much of a

00:34:34.200 --> 00:34:39.800
[Amit Varma]: problem for you was this at sort of conscious level? And my other sort of related question

00:34:39.800 --> 00:34:43.840
[Amit Varma]: goes back to what you were earlier saying about strategy and tactics, where I was reading

00:34:43.840 --> 00:34:48.840
[Amit Varma]: an interview of Rabasa. And Rabasa was asked the same question about strategy and tactics.

00:34:48.840 --> 00:34:53.360
[Amit Varma]: And he said, I have no strategy, it's only tactics. And perhaps there is a strategy he's

00:34:53.360 --> 00:34:57.520
[Amit Varma]: internalized in his processes or whatever, I'm guessing. But he said, it's only tactics,

00:34:57.520 --> 00:35:02.400
[Amit Varma]: I just go, you know, one sentence at a time, and so on. So how do you resolve that? Like

00:35:02.400 --> 00:35:06.360
[Amit Varma]: you interestingly said that you do have a strategy when you get down to. So what's this

00:35:06.360 --> 00:35:11.040
[Guest]: distinction between strategy and tactics? So strategy, I mean, when I say I have a strategy,

00:35:11.040 --> 00:35:17.200
[Guest]: I would say that I have an objective. And it is internalized, it is not that it varies

00:35:17.200 --> 00:35:21.600
[Guest]: from text to text, it is a, it is almost a philosophy of translation, or my philosophy

00:35:21.600 --> 00:35:28.640
[Guest]: of translation, if you like, which, as I keep saying, is about being faithful to the sum

00:35:28.640 --> 00:35:38.040
[Guest]: total of the text and the world it creates, as it is perceived by a reader. And my attempt

00:35:38.040 --> 00:35:44.160
[Guest]: is to read it like a universal reader or like a reader of without any particular objective

00:35:44.160 --> 00:35:48.560
[Guest]: in mind. A reader has no objective in reading, the reader is just reading. So every reader

00:35:48.560 --> 00:35:52.600
[Guest]: as it were, so my objective is to read it like every reader, and then make sure that

00:35:52.600 --> 00:35:58.000
[Guest]: the translation can be read by every reader with essentially the same kind of feelings

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:03.080
[Guest]: and notions and what they absorb and so on about it, as opposed to, let's say, I will

00:36:03.080 --> 00:36:08.720
[Guest]: be true to making sure that every word is taken across or every metaphor is taken across

00:36:08.720 --> 00:36:12.880
[Guest]: and so on. Now, this does not mean that you play with the text or you are reckless with

00:36:12.880 --> 00:36:19.200
[Guest]: it. It just means that then it comes down to specific tactics at a sentence level, at

00:36:19.200 --> 00:36:23.720
[Guest]: a word level, where you do what you think is best, keeping this overall overarching

00:36:23.720 --> 00:36:28.440
[Guest]: objective in mind. So sometimes an idiom will render itself beautifully in another language.

00:36:28.440 --> 00:36:33.760
[Guest]: There is no need to then say, I will not do it. Another time, it's absurd. And you say,

00:36:33.760 --> 00:36:37.240
[Guest]: I will not do it. A third time, it's absurd. And you say, I will do it because it's so

00:36:37.240 --> 00:36:41.800
[Guest]: picturesque and it draws up such a fantastic image that I don't want to sacrifice it, even

00:36:41.800 --> 00:36:46.820
[Guest]: if it doesn't roll off the tongue as easily. So that's tactics, right? And then ultimately,

00:36:46.820 --> 00:36:50.600
[Guest]: it's also not, you don't see it in isolation. You see where it stands in the scheme of the

00:36:50.600 --> 00:36:54.840
[Guest]: sentence, the paragraph, when you're reading it afterwards, is it jumping out at you like

00:36:54.840 --> 00:36:59.360
[Guest]: a sore thumb? Because that's something that I am completely against. You know, these islands

00:36:59.360 --> 00:37:04.640
[Guest]: of brilliance in a text are avoidable as long as they're not there in the original. And

00:37:04.640 --> 00:37:09.320
[Guest]: that also brings me to the point, you have to keep the flaws as well. You cannot paper

00:37:09.320 --> 00:37:14.760
[Guest]: over the flaws. If you see something as being clunky writing, and remember that Bangla literature

00:37:14.760 --> 00:37:20.320
[Guest]: was never edited. Only now is there a sort of semblance of editing, but nothing, there's

00:37:20.320 --> 00:37:24.040
[Amit Varma]: no structural edits, nothing. And often, I guess it would have been written at great

00:37:24.040 --> 00:37:28.520
[Guest]: speed for these magazines and all of that. That's right. So in fact, it's a wonder that

00:37:28.520 --> 00:37:33.640
[Guest]: our, and it's not just Bangla, all Indian languages, it's a wonder how good these literatures

00:37:33.640 --> 00:37:37.760
[Guest]: are, despite the fact that there is no editing. And if you're mischievous, you can always

00:37:37.760 --> 00:37:42.680
[Guest]: say it's because there is no editing. But I mean, I don't entirely agree with that.

00:37:42.680 --> 00:37:46.640
[Guest]: But yeah, so therefore, a lot of flaws. I mean, I would have edited Tagore, I would

00:37:46.640 --> 00:37:52.080
[Guest]: have edited the hell out of Tagore if I were his editor in Bangla. But, you know, so then

00:37:52.080 --> 00:37:56.680
[Guest]: you when you're translating, you have to keep some of those, not some, all, if you perceive

00:37:56.680 --> 00:38:00.200
[Guest]: weaknesses, you have to keep them. If you see clunkiness, you have to keep it.

00:38:00.200 --> 00:38:03.240
[Guest]: So are you deliberately recreating that clunkiness into English?

00:38:03.240 --> 00:38:07.320
[Guest]: Absolutely. If it's there in the Bangla, absolutely. And then the editor will say, can we change

00:38:07.320 --> 00:38:11.600
[Guest]: this? And I said, No, we can't because it's not in my control. This is what the writer

00:38:11.600 --> 00:38:16.680
[Guest]: wrote. I can't help it. And let him let the writer be read for, you know, their warts

00:38:16.680 --> 00:38:19.560
[Guest]: as well. Why should they be read only for what's great? So yeah.

00:38:19.560 --> 00:38:23.360
[Amit Varma]: No, and going back to, you know, something that Emily Wilson wrote, and Emily Wilson

00:38:23.360 --> 00:38:28.080
[Amit Varma]: wrote this in the context of Seneca, but it brought your Bengali translations to my mind

00:38:28.080 --> 00:38:33.480
[Amit Varma]: when I read it first, where she writes on translating Seneca, quote, I had a hard time

00:38:33.480 --> 00:38:38.680
[Amit Varma]: figuring out how much I could get away with pulling out all the stops rhetorically, because

00:38:38.680 --> 00:38:42.840
[Amit Varma]: she writes in this wonderfully ornate purple style. It's showing off, showing off, showing

00:38:42.840 --> 00:38:48.200
[Amit Varma]: off bombast. The risk is always that is going to come across as too silly to be impressive.

00:38:48.200 --> 00:38:53.040
[Amit Varma]: It has to go very close to sounding silly, but without quite getting the stop code. And

00:38:53.040 --> 00:38:58.960
[Amit Varma]: later she wrote a Twitter thread, which I'll reproduce in the show notes about all the

00:38:58.960 --> 00:39:04.120
[Amit Varma]: sort of the difficulties of translating Odyssey, Homer's Odyssey, which she did recently. And

00:39:04.120 --> 00:39:08.760
[Amit Varma]: part two of them might be very relevant to you, where she said that there aren't enough

00:39:08.760 --> 00:39:14.280
[Amit Varma]: onomatopoeic words for very loud chaotic noises. And Bengali is full of these, full of it.

00:39:14.280 --> 00:39:19.080
[Amit Varma]: Like, yeh toh jata bolshe, taki barabari hoyega lo, ha ha kode chute lo, ghatta kha kha kod

00:39:19.080 --> 00:39:24.120
[Amit Varma]: che, gaagiri kode utlo. And you know exactly, even if you don't know the meaning, you know

00:39:24.120 --> 00:39:28.200
[Amit Varma]: exactly what. How do you capture this flavor? Is it even possible? Or do you have to tactically

00:39:28.200 --> 00:39:33.920
[Guest]: decide to, you know? Yeah, I've started taking more risks now, to be honest. Originally,

00:39:33.920 --> 00:39:37.120
[Guest]: I would say, you know, I'm not going to put in words and phrases that will make no sense

00:39:37.120 --> 00:39:40.640
[Guest]: to the reader. But now I've started trying sometimes.

00:39:40.640 --> 00:39:43.760
[Guest]: Give me an example. So, you know, if it's ghatta kha kode utlo,

00:39:43.760 --> 00:39:48.520
[Guest]: which is basically that I was extremely annoyed and irritated and so on. So, I might actually

00:39:48.520 --> 00:39:55.840
[Guest]: say that, you know, an annoyed wave ran through her body or something like that, you know.

00:39:55.840 --> 00:40:00.320
[Guest]: But actually find a way to suggest that this is how it is used in the original language.

00:40:00.320 --> 00:40:04.200
[Guest]: And sometimes, you know, the reason I also do it, I think that if the language does not

00:40:04.200 --> 00:40:08.840
[Guest]: have this, maybe it deserves to have it. You know, so why not introduce, because we have

00:40:08.840 --> 00:40:14.720
[Guest]: done that, right? The English, any language grows by taking in terms for which no terms

00:40:14.720 --> 00:40:19.000
[Guest]: exist in its own. And because we are now living in an increasingly globalized world, you don't

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:23.720
[Guest]: have a choice but to represent many things which are not inherently part of the culture

00:40:23.720 --> 00:40:27.440
[Guest]: from which your language came. So, what do you do then? I mean, we do it in India all

00:40:27.440 --> 00:40:31.880
[Guest]: the time. We're forever borrowing English words. So, why not the other way around?

00:40:31.880 --> 00:40:36.320
[Amit Varma]: No, and in fact, translation in a sense has also been described, I forget by who, has

00:40:36.320 --> 00:40:41.000
[Amit Varma]: also been described as a dialogue between languages. And is that something you felt

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:42.000
[Amit Varma]: cutely while?

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:47.920
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah. The good thing, perhaps the best thing about all of this discourse is that

00:40:47.920 --> 00:40:53.420
[Guest]: you can happily get into it after the translation is done. It does not have to actually intrude

00:40:53.420 --> 00:40:57.040
[Guest]: on the act of translating itself, because then you'd be a shit critic, you wouldn't

00:40:57.040 --> 00:41:01.680
[Guest]: be able to finish a line if you kept putting so much thought into, so much thought of this

00:41:01.680 --> 00:41:07.320
[Guest]: kind into it. But yeah, I'm eternally, like I have this new theory now of literature,

00:41:07.320 --> 00:41:11.120
[Guest]: of translations and so on, which is that, I know we keep saying the original language

00:41:11.120 --> 00:41:14.920
[Guest]: and then the target language and so on. My theory is that there is no original language

00:41:14.920 --> 00:41:20.560
[Guest]: in which a work exists. A work exists outside of language and it springs into being in each

00:41:20.560 --> 00:41:26.160
[Guest]: language at the time in which it is written. So, even if it so turns out that the Bengali

00:41:26.160 --> 00:41:31.520
[Guest]: version was written first chronologically, it does not mean that the English version

00:41:31.520 --> 00:41:37.040
[Guest]: is a version of the Bengali version. Both the Bengali and the English are versions of

00:41:37.040 --> 00:41:42.880
[Guest]: that pure thing which exists up there, which the writer pulled out of their own head and

00:41:42.880 --> 00:41:48.240
[Guest]: everything and put into words in a particular linguistic system. They could just as well

00:41:48.240 --> 00:41:52.720
[Guest]: have done it in another linguistic system, depending on which one they were familiar

00:41:52.720 --> 00:41:57.840
[Guest]: with. And that, therefore, the work does not spring up only in that one particular language.

00:41:57.840 --> 00:42:02.680
[Guest]: It can exist in all languages. This is one of those clever, you know, things to think

00:42:02.680 --> 00:42:03.680
[Amit Varma]: about.

00:42:03.680 --> 00:42:06.480
[Amit Varma]: This reminds me of something Octavio Paz once said, where he said, quote, when we learn

00:42:06.480 --> 00:42:11.680
[Guest]: to speak, we are learning to translate, stop quote, which is exactly what you just said.

00:42:11.680 --> 00:42:16.080
[Guest]: But I'm saying that this is a slightly clever thing because I also equally will argue for

00:42:16.080 --> 00:42:23.240
[Guest]: the fact that you cannot actually divorce the content of a text from the language. The

00:42:23.240 --> 00:42:27.480
[Guest]: language determines the content even, you know, because certain things, you cannot put

00:42:27.480 --> 00:42:29.200
[Guest]: it in that language, they're not in the text.

00:42:29.200 --> 00:42:31.640
[Guest]: I agree with that, yeah.

00:42:31.640 --> 00:42:35.240
[Guest]: And therefore, some books cannot be written in some languages. Because there's things

00:42:35.240 --> 00:42:38.360
[Guest]: that need to go into that book, perhaps cannot be put into English, you have to write it

00:42:38.360 --> 00:42:42.440
[Guest]: in Hindi or Bangla or Urdu. So, you know, and I'm saying that these are theories and

00:42:42.440 --> 00:42:47.400
[Guest]: theories don't necessarily have to map on to any kind of reality. A theory is after

00:42:47.400 --> 00:42:53.560
[Guest]: all what? It is a way of examining a phenomenon and seeing what patterns you can discern in

00:42:53.560 --> 00:42:54.560
[Guest]: it.

00:42:54.560 --> 00:42:58.720
[Guest]: That does not mean that alternative theories cannot do an equally good job of discerning

00:42:58.720 --> 00:43:02.840
[Guest]: patterns or explaining it. And part of the beauty of it is that you don't eventually

00:43:02.840 --> 00:43:07.720
[Guest]: need, it's not science, so you don't need one all encompassing theory to explain it

00:43:07.720 --> 00:43:12.400
[Guest]: because the purpose of that theory is to then also predict that if this is the input, this

00:43:12.400 --> 00:43:16.400
[Guest]: will always be the output. And essentially, literature and art and translation are not

00:43:16.400 --> 00:43:20.920
[Guest]: about same input producing same output. If that were the case, then every translation

00:43:20.920 --> 00:43:25.720
[Guest]: would be the same. It's not. So, someone is mediating, someone is mediating with who knows

00:43:25.720 --> 00:43:30.560
[Guest]: what kind of agendas that even they don't know. As a translator, I'm sure there are

00:43:30.560 --> 00:43:36.160
[Guest]: things going on in my subconscious and unconscious that I'm not aware of. As a translator, I

00:43:36.160 --> 00:43:40.360
[Guest]: know I've evolved, every translator evolves. So, the way you translate a text, if I were

00:43:40.360 --> 00:43:45.200
[Guest]: to go back and translate the text that I translated 10 years ago, I am certain they would be different.

00:43:45.200 --> 00:43:51.000
[Amit Varma]: No, and what I also find fascinating is that while you are someone who now teaches writing,

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:55.960
[Amit Varma]: who teaches literature, who teaches translation, you were first a practitioner. The theorizing

00:43:55.960 --> 00:43:56.960
[Guest]: has come later.

00:43:56.960 --> 00:44:01.640
[Guest]: The theorizing has come later, but I don't teach translation theory. I just, I mean,

00:44:01.640 --> 00:44:07.080
[Guest]: these questions come up in the course of actually performing translations. So, then we answer

00:44:07.080 --> 00:44:10.480
[Guest]: them and then sometimes we get carried away and start constructing theories because it's

00:44:10.480 --> 00:44:14.920
[Guest]: fun to do and interesting things to discuss and write about. To be honest, I see translation

00:44:14.920 --> 00:44:21.600
[Guest]: theory as a very valuable but distinct space from the practice of translation, the praxis

00:44:21.600 --> 00:44:22.600
[Amit Varma]: of translation.

