00:45:54.320 --> 00:45:59.080
[Amit Varma]: of got back just before we went to the break. So, you know, another thing that strikes me,

00:45:59.080 --> 00:46:03.880
[Amit Varma]: and this is something that other translators across the world have pointed out, is of English

00:46:03.880 --> 00:46:09.200
[Amit Varma]: sort of being a bridge language between languages, that very often English is the first language

00:46:09.200 --> 00:46:14.400
[Amit Varma]: that something will be translated into. And quite often, it will become the source of

00:46:14.400 --> 00:46:19.720
[Amit Varma]: translation for further languages. So, for example, language one is translated into English,

00:46:19.720 --> 00:46:24.840
[Amit Varma]: and then language one is further translated into language two via the English translation.

00:46:24.840 --> 00:46:29.700
[Amit Varma]: So English almost has a sort of a central role. And this is, of course, in the context

00:46:29.700 --> 00:46:34.800
[Amit Varma]: of world literature, but even in the context of India, you know, English is sort of where,

00:46:34.800 --> 00:46:39.820
[Amit Varma]: you know, there's a whole publishing industry in English. How has the ecosystem there evolved

00:46:39.820 --> 00:46:45.160
[Amit Varma]: in terms of languages getting translated into English into each other? What is the importance

00:46:45.160 --> 00:46:49.440
[Amit Varma]: of English in spreading, popularising our literature in other languages?

00:46:49.440 --> 00:46:52.120
[Guest]: Sajeevan Gupta So if you mean around the world outside of

00:46:52.120 --> 00:46:57.840
[Guest]: India, yeah, yeah. So outside of India, it is, of course, crucial, because this is it's

00:46:57.840 --> 00:47:04.360
[Guest]: the language that your most translators working into. So it's much harder to find translators

00:47:04.360 --> 00:47:08.320
[Guest]: who will translate, let's say, a Bangla text into French or German or Spanish, right? There'll

00:47:08.320 --> 00:47:12.720
[Guest]: be one or two or three people. So there are only so many texts they can do. So English

00:47:12.720 --> 00:47:18.080
[Guest]: automatically becomes the receptacle, as it were, of the translations. And then because

00:47:18.080 --> 00:47:22.120
[Guest]: as you said, it is the language that lubricates global publishing. So people will read the

00:47:22.120 --> 00:47:27.520
[Guest]: English version and then maybe decide to publish it in another language. And more often than

00:47:27.520 --> 00:47:32.880
[Guest]: not, they might well use the English edition as the source, because they don't have translators

00:47:32.880 --> 00:47:38.960
[Guest]: working between the original first and the new languages. It's not the best situation.

00:47:38.960 --> 00:47:43.160
[Guest]: But to my mind, it's better than no situation. I mean, I always feel that any translation

00:47:43.160 --> 00:47:48.800
[Guest]: is better than no translation. So we have to lump it even if we don't like it. In India,

00:47:48.800 --> 00:47:54.200
[Guest]: it's the same and even worse in some ways, because people who now are genuinely biliterate

00:47:54.200 --> 00:47:58.560
[Guest]: in two non-English languages from India are very hard to find. You had a whole bunch of

00:47:58.560 --> 00:48:04.920
[Guest]: them earlier. For one thing, you know, there were large scale migrations in India of people

00:48:04.920 --> 00:48:09.880
[Guest]: from particular communities into other spaces and who then had to first learn the local

00:48:09.880 --> 00:48:13.800
[Guest]: language. So very interestingly, a legacy of that is one of the best translators working

00:48:13.800 --> 00:48:19.240
[Guest]: from Bangla into English is actually a Tamil. His name is Ramakrishnan. But you wouldn't

00:48:19.240 --> 00:48:23.920
[Guest]: know that except for the fact that his name is Ramakrishnan and his Bangla is fantastic.

00:48:23.920 --> 00:48:27.720
[Guest]: And I dare say he could translate into Tamil if his Tamil was good enough. But people like

00:48:27.720 --> 00:48:33.400
[Guest]: that are almost impossible to find. No one picks up another language anymore. At best,

00:48:33.400 --> 00:48:37.880
[Guest]: you have to learn it to be able to go into translation and then nobody is interested

00:48:37.880 --> 00:48:43.260
[Guest]: in going into translation, you know, between Indian languages. So, but first we are moving

00:48:43.260 --> 00:48:48.160
[Guest]: to a situation where English will become the fulcrum and from there, you know, the arms

00:48:48.160 --> 00:48:53.120
[Guest]: will poke out in different directions. And I feel it's better than nothing, because at

00:48:53.120 --> 00:48:57.560
[Guest]: least there are so many good literatures in India and such fantastic books being written

00:48:57.560 --> 00:49:01.680
[Guest]: in at least a dozen languages, that it would be a shame if they could not be read by people

00:49:01.680 --> 00:49:07.200
[Guest]: who read other languages and don't want to read them in English or do not read English.

00:49:07.200 --> 00:49:11.640
[Amit Varma]: And even an imperfect translation, if it conveys some of what is good about the original can

00:49:11.640 --> 00:49:15.960
[Amit Varma]: spur the reader to look for more and maybe do the work herself. Absolutely, absolutely.

00:49:15.960 --> 00:49:20.520
[Guest]: That's what I'm saying. A bad translation is better than no translation, quite honestly,

00:49:20.520 --> 00:49:27.000
[Amit Varma]: if the original work is really good. And also does, you know, given that language affects

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:31.960
[Amit Varma]: thinking, like one, would you agree that language affects thinking as, or we'll keep saying,

00:49:31.960 --> 00:49:37.720
[Amit Varma]: and two, would you then say that our thinking can become homogenous and Englishified if

00:49:37.720 --> 00:49:42.920
[Amit Varma]: that becomes sort of the universal language of use? Now, I don't know if I'll be sort

00:49:42.920 --> 00:49:47.920
[Amit Varma]: of able to express it well, but for example, one question I half seriously sometimes pose

00:49:47.920 --> 00:49:53.360
[Amit Varma]: to people is that do Hindi speakers think differently because there isn't a semicolon

00:49:53.360 --> 00:49:58.280
[Guest]: in the language? You know, if that makes any kind of sense. I know what you mean. But I

00:49:58.280 --> 00:50:02.560
[Guest]: think the way I see it is that those of us who are born in India actually have the unique

00:50:02.560 --> 00:50:08.160
[Guest]: privilege of being able to code switch fairly. At least those who also use English are able

00:50:08.160 --> 00:50:13.320
[Guest]: to code switch at their convenience and therefore they switch to the language that best accommodates

00:50:13.320 --> 00:50:18.440
[Guest]: their thoughts. I don't think no matter how much English spreads, our thought is limited

00:50:18.440 --> 00:50:24.760
[Guest]: by what English can or cannot do. We very happily use words from our own language and

00:50:24.760 --> 00:50:29.320
[Guest]: from other languages across India for that matter. And then we sort of shown them into

00:50:29.320 --> 00:50:35.560
[Guest]: the English quite seamlessly to the extent that if you hear the way English is now spoken,

00:50:35.560 --> 00:50:41.120
[Guest]: for example, across streets, it's quite different. In fact, you know, to me, the best example

00:50:41.120 --> 00:50:47.880
[Guest]: of the way English is used unselfconsciously with massive borrowings from Indian words

00:50:47.880 --> 00:50:54.600
[Guest]: is pornography. If you read in English pornography written in India, you will find that obviously

00:50:54.600 --> 00:51:00.080
[Guest]: there is no attempt at any pristine literary values. So therefore, the word that best suits

00:51:00.080 --> 00:51:04.880
[Guest]: the situation is used no matter which language it belongs to. While the fluid is primarily

00:51:04.880 --> 00:51:09.760
[Guest]: English, but it's mixed with all kinds of things. It's also interesting that even English

00:51:09.760 --> 00:51:17.040
[Guest]: is misused in the sense, for example, that instead of lay, lay as in lie down, it will

00:51:17.040 --> 00:51:24.240
[Guest]: always be the word in English will often be sleep. So it will be a man will often say

00:51:24.240 --> 00:51:31.320
[Guest]: write something like I slept on her. You see where it's coming from. It's very interesting

00:51:31.320 --> 00:51:35.800
[Guest]: that the thought originates in another language and there is a sort of futile attempt to translate

00:51:35.800 --> 00:51:41.280
[Guest]: it into the English equivalent, literally, so that you end up with a rather comic kind

00:51:41.280 --> 00:51:46.280
[Guest]: of image if you want to, but it is fearless. The way the language is treated in pornography

00:51:46.280 --> 00:51:52.760
[Guest]: is absolutely fearless. And because I did say there is a range of activities and impulses

00:51:52.760 --> 00:51:59.720
[Guest]: that you're trying to portray, you cannot be sort of, you know, bowed down by the limitations

00:51:59.720 --> 00:52:09.200
[Guest]: of your medium. So in the same way, I think the English that I hear is a brilliant combination

00:52:09.200 --> 00:52:11.880
[Guest]: of the best of many different languages.

00:52:11.880 --> 00:52:16.320
[Amit Varma]: And what you just said, like from the limited in the limited erotica that I have read, Indian

00:52:16.320 --> 00:52:21.200
[Amit Varma]: erotica in English that I have read that category, I've never noticed any such thing. So which

00:52:21.200 --> 00:52:27.280
[Amit Varma]: kind of makes me wonder that because you're looking at language so carefully being a translator,

00:52:27.280 --> 00:52:29.280
[Amit Varma]: do you also notice all of these things?

00:52:29.280 --> 00:52:33.520
[Guest]: Quite possibly. I think that's entirely right. And you know, it can be an annoyance sometimes

00:52:33.520 --> 00:52:40.400
[Guest]: because you're both marvelling and being annoyed by what you're reading, no matter what. So

00:52:40.400 --> 00:52:45.320
[Guest]: when I read English, for example, I'm always thinking, oh, man, this sentence is so good.

00:52:45.320 --> 00:52:50.080
[Guest]: And why can't I translate a sentence as good? Whether what I'm reading is a translation

00:52:50.080 --> 00:52:55.160
[Guest]: or not. And when I'm reading Bangla, I keep thinking, oh, no. So what if I had to translate

00:52:55.160 --> 00:52:59.680
[Guest]: this? Would I ever be able to do it? Or what a lousy sentence, you know, how am I going

00:52:59.680 --> 00:53:05.440
[Guest]: to put any kind of value into this sentence? So it's annoying. It's like a meta commentary

00:53:05.440 --> 00:53:07.480
[Guest]: that is always running through your head.

00:53:07.480 --> 00:53:13.800
[Amit Varma]: No, and just like thinking aloud, like I deplore language Nazis, because as far as I'm concerned,

00:53:13.800 --> 00:53:18.040
[Amit Varma]: language evolves. New words come in all the time. For example, people frown on the use

00:53:18.040 --> 00:53:22.680
[Amit Varma]: of the Indian English neologism, prepone. But I think prepone is a great word. It's

00:53:22.680 --> 00:53:24.360
[Amit Varma]: a very elegant word for the use.

00:53:24.360 --> 00:53:26.000
[Amit Varma]: It's a very economical word.

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:31.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's a very nice word. Why would you say it longer? And it's obvious what it means.

00:53:31.320 --> 00:53:36.040
[Amit Varma]: And because of the sheer population of English speakers in India, is it then possible that

00:53:36.040 --> 00:53:40.640
[Amit Varma]: the future of the English language will be driven by all the contortions which we carry

00:53:40.640 --> 00:53:42.360
[Amit Varma]: out with the like sleeping on?

00:53:42.360 --> 00:53:47.080
[Guest]: Maybe in India, it will, I don't think it'll spread across the world. I mean, for example,

00:53:47.080 --> 00:53:53.080
[Guest]: here in India, we have no idea of the African flavours of English, or the Caribbean flavours

00:53:53.080 --> 00:53:56.280
[Guest]: of English. And yet those are very, very distinct in those spaces.

00:53:56.280 --> 00:54:00.120
[Amit Varma]: In fact, William Carlos Williams once said that I don't write in English, I write in

00:54:00.120 --> 00:54:06.680
[Amit Varma]: the American idiom, which obviously also creates then additional problems for translators.

00:54:06.680 --> 00:54:12.800
[Amit Varma]: Now, you've also sort of, you've translated writers from like Bong Kim, who are much older,

00:54:12.800 --> 00:54:17.720
[Amit Varma]: you're translating people like Nauberon. And obviously, the idioms that they are writing

00:54:17.720 --> 00:54:21.800
[Amit Varma]: in the times that they have inhabited the slang and the language they use is very, very

00:54:21.800 --> 00:54:27.200
[Amit Varma]: different. So, how do you sort of how, how easy or hard is it to deal with something

00:54:27.200 --> 00:54:28.200
[Guest]: like that?

00:54:28.200 --> 00:54:32.920
[Guest]: It's not easy. I mean, it's easier to deal with modern and contemporary, it's definitely

00:54:32.920 --> 00:54:35.000
[Amit Varma]: harder to deal with classic text.

00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:38.880
[Amit Varma]: So when you're translating someone like Bong Kim, and a phrasing of his seems archaic in

00:54:38.880 --> 00:54:43.720
[Amit Varma]: the original Bengali, will you then also attempt to reproduce that archaicness in the English?

00:54:43.720 --> 00:54:50.880
[Guest]: I will not in the way in which you might read it in say, a Victorian novel or in an Arthur

00:54:50.880 --> 00:54:56.560
[Guest]: Conan Doyle story? No, because I think that will not sit easily on me. But I will try

00:54:56.560 --> 00:55:01.400
[Guest]: to bring out what we think of as archaic as a certain quaint elegance. And I think that

00:55:01.400 --> 00:55:07.320
[Guest]: is what I would aim for. Yeah, so I might not use certain words, which were very prevalent

00:55:07.320 --> 00:55:12.240
[Guest]: when you were writing in English in the 19th century. Because after all, I, you know, the

00:55:12.240 --> 00:55:17.000
[Guest]: translation is being done in 2020, or whenever, it is not being done 100 years ago. And indeed,

00:55:17.000 --> 00:55:21.280
[Guest]: if I read translations of those words done 100 years ago, you can see that they use what

00:55:21.280 --> 00:55:25.080
[Guest]: is contemporary English. But see, there's this other factor there, which is this, that

00:55:25.080 --> 00:55:30.320
[Guest]: Bungim take the first novel that he wrote in Bangla, Durgesh Nandini, which I've translated,

00:55:30.320 --> 00:55:37.480
[Guest]: he was 26. Bungim Chandra Chattopadhyay is 26 at the time, 26. Okay, that's it. He is,

00:55:37.480 --> 00:55:41.880
[Guest]: he has written an English novel, which has bombed, so to speak, and he himself is unsure

00:55:41.880 --> 00:55:45.920
[Guest]: of his ideological moorings in having made that choice. So he writes this tremendously

00:55:45.920 --> 00:55:52.880
[Guest]: racy romance. It's in the Walter Scott mold, right? It's racy, it's full of, I mean, it's

00:55:52.880 --> 00:55:56.720
[Guest]: everything that you would want to read in a historical romance. But he's writing it

00:55:56.720 --> 00:56:00.840
[Guest]: for a contemporary audience, although he's setting it in his past. He's setting it several

00:56:00.840 --> 00:56:04.560
[Guest]: hundred years ago from the time he lives in, but he's still writing it in a contemporary

00:56:04.560 --> 00:56:10.400
[Guest]: idiom. Now that contemporary idiom 100 years later appears very archaic. But am I being

00:56:10.400 --> 00:56:16.960
[Guest]: true to that text if I were to use a very archaic mode for it? Because a 26 year old

00:56:16.960 --> 00:56:21.440
[Guest]: writing for a contemporary audience, should I not try to create something of that effect,

00:56:21.440 --> 00:56:26.160
[Guest]: not by being faddish, because those terms will come today and go tomorrow, but in keeping

00:56:26.160 --> 00:56:33.800
[Guest]: some sense of modernity about it. And so you aim, therefore, for a more timeless kind of

00:56:33.800 --> 00:56:38.520
[Guest]: approach, you know, which is where your idioms are not rooted in a particular space or time

00:56:38.520 --> 00:56:44.280
[Guest]: or anything. But you try to bring out the notion that it should be read without the

00:56:44.280 --> 00:56:49.040
[Guest]: degree of difficulty that we now encounter in reading the Bangla. And that's a very interesting

00:56:49.040 --> 00:56:53.760
[Guest]: question always. And an interesting theoretical question, if you're looking at an older text,

00:56:53.760 --> 00:56:59.560
[Guest]: which is that should you reproduce the reader's response as it was when the text came out?

00:56:59.560 --> 00:57:04.200
[Guest]: Or should you reproduce the reader's response now if they were to read the original text?

00:57:04.200 --> 00:57:08.720
[Guest]: And to me, frankly, reading Bumkim Chandra original in Bangla is like reading it in translation,

00:57:08.720 --> 00:57:14.840
[Guest]: not reading a foreign language in many ways. I mean, the words may be familiar or not even,

00:57:14.840 --> 00:57:20.160
[Guest]: but the structures, the whole flow are clearly from another era. And, you know, like they

00:57:20.160 --> 00:57:25.200
[Guest]: say, the past is a foreign country. So it is no different from, you know, when we say

00:57:25.200 --> 00:57:30.440
[Guest]: that this work is in Bangla, just because it uses the Bangla script and certain familiar

00:57:30.440 --> 00:57:37.960
[Guest]: words, we are actually papering over huge differences in register. Huge, enormous. So,

00:57:37.960 --> 00:57:40.080
[Guest]: you know, these are things to be factored in for sure.

00:57:40.080 --> 00:57:45.040
[Amit Varma]: And, and how does it, and especially with the contemporary guys, how do you deal with

00:57:45.040 --> 00:57:50.080
[Amit Varma]: dialogue? For example, Edith Grossman writes about dialogue, quote, dialogue contains often

00:57:50.080 --> 00:57:55.000
[Amit Varma]: nuance or sometimes egregious indications of the class status and education of the characters,

00:57:55.000 --> 00:57:59.900
[Amit Varma]: not to mention the intelligence and emotional state, significant intentions and sonorities

00:57:59.900 --> 00:58:04.120
[Amit Varma]: abound in the narration and in the descriptive portions of the work. There may be elements

00:58:04.120 --> 00:58:10.640
[Amit Varma]: of irony or satire, the rhythm of the prose, long flowing periods or short crisp phrases,

00:58:10.640 --> 00:58:15.480
[Amit Varma]: and the tone of the writing, colloquialisms, elevated diction, pomposity, slang, elegance,

00:58:15.480 --> 00:58:20.520
[Amit Varma]: substandard use, are pivotal stylistic devices. And it is incumbent upon the translator to

00:58:20.520 --> 00:58:25.640
[Amit Varma]: apprehend the ways in which these instrumentalities further the purposes of the fiction, the revolution

00:58:25.640 --> 00:58:28.600
[Amit Varma]: of character, the progress of the action, stop quote.

00:58:28.600 --> 00:58:33.440
[Amit Varma]: And here it strikes me that, you know, when it comes to a novel itself, you know, I guess

00:58:33.440 --> 00:58:39.240
[Amit Varma]: you go through that original moment of discovering what the voice is, and then you can continue

00:58:39.240 --> 00:58:43.000
[Amit Varma]: with the authorial voice for the whole of the book once you've sort of slipped into

00:58:43.000 --> 00:58:48.080
[Amit Varma]: that voice. But when it comes to the dialogue within a book where you have different people

00:58:48.080 --> 00:58:52.440
[Amit Varma]: speaking in all of these different kinds of languages, in some cases written by people,

00:58:52.440 --> 00:58:58.040
[Amit Varma]: perhaps much younger than you today in settings you haven't inhabited yourself, is that harder?

00:58:58.040 --> 00:59:00.560
[Guest]: How do you get around that? It is. And it's not just that. It's also,

00:59:00.560 --> 00:59:04.720
[Guest]: for example, and this is probably true of all languages in all Indian languages as well,

00:59:04.720 --> 00:59:08.680
[Guest]: which is that you have many dialects and many local variations. And many authors are very

00:59:08.680 --> 00:59:13.800
[Guest]: good with reproducing the speech. If you take even an urban setting, which is a confluence

00:59:13.800 --> 00:59:18.720
[Guest]: of people of different socioeconomic backgrounds, then each one is speaking in a different register,

00:59:18.720 --> 00:59:22.880
[Guest]: very clearly different vocabulary, different ways, pronunciations and so on. And you cannot

00:59:22.880 --> 00:59:28.280
[Guest]: actually bring all of that into English for the simple reason that if you were to choose,

00:59:28.280 --> 00:59:33.640
[Guest]: first of all, your choice of English dialects or versions of English would be purely random.

00:59:33.640 --> 00:59:40.280
[Guest]: So I've actually read translations where a certain village dialect has been translated

00:59:40.280 --> 00:59:46.040
[Guest]: into a Scottish version of English. How does that even work? Because in fact, on the contrary,

00:59:46.040 --> 00:59:50.480
[Guest]: you're creating in the reader who identifies it as a Scottish brogue, a false sense of

00:59:50.480 --> 00:59:56.240
[Guest]: space. It's not correct at all. So this is a very, very difficult situation, especially

00:59:56.240 --> 01:00:00.000
[Guest]: when there's a clash. Let's say when people are speaking the same dialect, then it's not

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:03.920
[Guest]: such a problem because they're perfectly intelligible to each other. So even if you were to put

01:00:03.920 --> 01:00:08.160
[Guest]: them in standard English, it would not matter. The problem is when, so you know, classic

01:00:08.160 --> 01:00:12.380
[Guest]: thing is that the guy who drives your car is talking to you. So you're speaking a kind

01:00:12.380 --> 01:00:17.400
[Guest]: of language which is very different from theirs. And you have to translate this while maintaining

01:00:17.400 --> 01:00:23.600
[Guest]: the difference in register. So it gets tough. And I would say that you don't always succeed.

01:00:23.600 --> 01:00:28.400
[Guest]: You try to do it with the words you use and so on. The other things that Irith Grossman

01:00:28.400 --> 01:00:35.080
[Guest]: talks about, you know, rhythm, music, and so on, those are easier to, or let me put

01:00:35.080 --> 01:00:39.280
[Guest]: it this way, if you're sensitive, if you can hear them, then you can perhaps take them

01:00:39.280 --> 01:00:41.760
[Amit Varma]: across. In fact, you said in the past that you read

01:00:41.760 --> 01:00:46.720
[Amit Varma]: out both the original and your translation of it to get a sense. So is it important to

01:00:46.720 --> 01:00:50.600
[Guest]: you that rhythmically and all that? Yes, it's very important to me. That is absolutely

01:00:50.600 --> 01:00:55.480
[Guest]: very important to me. But there again, you have problems. For example, in Bangla, it's

01:00:55.480 --> 01:01:00.800
[Guest]: very natural to have short sentences. The same structure in English creates a tremendously

01:01:00.800 --> 01:01:06.200
[Guest]: staccato feeling. Sometimes in Bangla, you generate tension with short sentences. In

01:01:06.200 --> 01:01:11.080
[Guest]: English, you actually have to use a longer sentence to generate the same kind of tension.

01:01:11.080 --> 01:01:16.160
[Guest]: So can you give me an example? So you know, this pulp writer named Shopan Kumar, whose

01:01:16.160 --> 01:01:21.240
[Guest]: work I've translated, so his work starts, and this is almost a cliche, and may not actually

01:01:21.240 --> 01:01:25.080
[Guest]: be there. It's like one of those excellent said, I elementary said he kind of things.

01:01:25.080 --> 01:01:30.760
[Guest]: But it goes like, ghorite dhong dhong kore, akta bajlo. And the big joke is, if it's akta

01:01:30.760 --> 01:01:34.760
[Guest]: one o'clock, then there should be only one, chime should be heard only once. So what is

01:01:34.760 --> 01:01:40.160
[Guest]: this dhong dhong business and so on. Or he has things like, you know, akate bonduk, akate

01:01:40.160 --> 01:01:48.560
[Guest]: cigarette, akate bohi nahi hai unni duklen. So other than that, so it's like, govir raat,

01:01:48.560 --> 01:01:52.320
[Guest]: brishti pochche, rasta ekta aulok nahi. So you get the sense, right?

01:01:52.320 --> 01:01:53.320
[Amit Varma]: In English, it's very staccato.

01:01:53.320 --> 01:01:58.680
[Guest]: In English, you make it as, yeah, dead at night, it's raining, not a person. It does

01:01:58.680 --> 01:02:02.560
[Guest]: not create the same kind of, but here it's almost breathless, the way it's described.

01:02:02.560 --> 01:02:06.160
[Guest]: So you know, there, you may have to combine them into a single sentence and find a way

01:02:06.160 --> 01:02:13.200
[Guest]: to keep it taught without using too many words. And sometimes you do that thing that many

01:02:13.200 --> 01:02:17.400
[Guest]: English grammar najis hate, which is comma splicing, which does not exist in English,

01:02:17.400 --> 01:02:21.120
[Guest]: right? You're supposed to use a semicolon or break it into two sentences.

01:02:21.120 --> 01:02:26.120
[Guest]: If you want it to exist, language evolves, people use it, it's fine.

01:02:26.120 --> 01:02:30.920
[Guest]: Now I find, in fact, I've been, one of the things I do is read translations of from European

01:02:30.920 --> 01:02:35.640
[Guest]: text very closely to see if they're comma splicing or not. And I find that some do and

01:02:35.640 --> 01:02:36.640
[Guest]: some don't.

01:02:36.640 --> 01:02:40.720
[Guest]: So then I went back to the translator as it was the story. And some of them said, I hate

01:02:40.720 --> 01:02:44.440
[Guest]: comma splicing, so I will not use it. And the other one says, no, no, the original has

01:02:44.440 --> 01:02:49.080
[Guest]: the rhythm, so I have to use it, even if I don't do it in my own writing.

01:02:49.080 --> 01:02:53.460
[Guest]: So people do have their quirks as well, you know, which translators' quirks also flow

01:02:53.460 --> 01:02:57.760
[Guest]: into their work somehow. But yeah, so what she's talking about, the rhythm and music

01:02:57.760 --> 01:03:02.560
[Guest]: and sounds, assonance, alliteration, these are still possible to manage. I mean, the

01:03:02.560 --> 01:03:06.760
[Guest]: most brilliant exponent of this, of course, is Anthea Bell in her translations of the

01:03:06.760 --> 01:03:11.480
[Guest]: Asterix comics. And very interestingly, her strategy, well, okay, let me not use the word

01:03:11.480 --> 01:03:17.120
[Guest]: strategy, her method there was that she would ensure that there were as many puns on a page

01:03:17.120 --> 01:03:20.560
[Guest]: of the English translation as there were in the original French.

01:03:20.560 --> 01:03:25.760
[Guest]: But not necessarily the same equivalent puns or not necessarily the same words being punned

01:03:25.760 --> 01:03:29.440
[Guest]: on. So if there was a pun in a panel, she would have a pun in the panel, but the pun

01:03:29.440 --> 01:03:34.720
[Guest]: might be on a different word altogether, because English would adopt, accept that pun and not

01:03:34.720 --> 01:03:39.960
[Guest]: the first one. So these are things that you have to do. But it's when people start speaking

01:03:39.960 --> 01:03:44.360
[Guest]: in different, for example, you know, when we read the Asterix comics, we have no sense

01:03:44.360 --> 01:03:50.840
[Guest]: of whether there's a different register that, I mean, Caesar sounds the same as, as Obelix,

01:03:50.840 --> 01:03:56.440
[Guest]: for example, right? The only difference might be in the choice of words or in how sonorous

01:03:56.440 --> 01:04:04.600
[Guest]: Caesar is, whereas Obelix is much more crisp or maybe excited and aggrieved for not getting

01:04:04.600 --> 01:04:10.560
[Guest]: the magic potion. So that's how you take it across. But you cannot actually convey the

01:04:10.560 --> 01:04:17.080
[Guest]: unstated information in used in the choice of dialect to the reader who understands and

01:04:17.080 --> 01:04:20.840
[Guest]: many readers will not even get nuances there. All they will know that, okay, this guy is

01:04:20.840 --> 01:04:25.640
[Guest]: not speaking standard Bangla. So therefore, from a different section, but they can't look

01:04:25.640 --> 01:04:30.800
[Guest]: at which section or where and so on. For that, you need a tremendously more discerning ear.

01:04:30.800 --> 01:04:36.000
[Guest]: So that information you're not always able to convey in your translation. And that's

01:04:36.000 --> 01:04:41.160
[Guest]: a problem, perhaps, in some cases. In other cases, it may not matter, because even if

01:04:41.160 --> 01:04:43.800
[Guest]: you convey the information, it will not mean anything to the reader.

01:04:43.800 --> 01:04:49.760
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, it seems to me that the most intense illustration of the difficulties of

01:04:49.760 --> 01:04:54.680
[Amit Varma]: translating actually comes from poetry, like Robert Frost controversially said that poetry

01:04:54.680 --> 01:04:59.840
[Amit Varma]: is a thing that gets lost in translation. And I was reading John Felstiner's book, Translating

01:04:59.840 --> 01:05:04.920
[Amit Varma]: Neruda, where he talks about that experience. And he writes, quote, bring over a poem's

01:05:04.920 --> 01:05:10.320
[Amit Varma]: ideas and images, and you will lose this manner. Imitate prosodic effects and you sacrifice

01:05:10.320 --> 01:05:14.520
[Amit Varma]: this matter. Get the letter and you miss the spirit, which is everything in poetry, or

01:05:14.520 --> 01:05:18.640
[Amit Varma]: get the spirit and you miss the letter, which is everything in poetry. But these are false

01:05:18.640 --> 01:05:24.640
[Amit Varma]: dilemmas. Worse translation at its best generates a wholly new utterance in the second language

01:05:24.640 --> 01:05:30.120
[Amit Varma]: new yet equivalent of equal value, stop quote. And have you tried your hand at poetry?

01:05:30.120 --> 01:05:34.640
[Guest]: Yeah, I've done poetry. I've done poetry. And it is true that translating poetry is

01:05:34.640 --> 01:05:39.600
[Guest]: a whole different ballgame. And indeed, if you keep this, that goes, and so on. And you

01:05:39.600 --> 01:05:44.120
[Guest]: might have to make some sacrifices. But equally, I agree that you are aiming to write poetry

01:05:44.120 --> 01:05:50.320
[Guest]: in the new language. And I would actually say that translating poetry is a little bit

01:05:50.320 --> 01:05:55.680
[Guest]: like doing a cover version of a song, you know, where the artist's own voice and manner

01:05:55.680 --> 01:06:00.200
[Amit Varma]: of singing will come to a good cover version will also be an original in a sense, it will

01:06:00.200 --> 01:06:05.160
[Guest]: be an original, it will stick to the melody, but it will improvise. And it will very clearly

01:06:05.160 --> 01:06:09.680
[Guest]: be rendered in the artist's voice and not in an attempt to replicate. I mean, those

01:06:09.680 --> 01:06:12.840
[Guest]: covers like when you sing exactly like the original, actually, the cover versions are

01:06:12.840 --> 01:06:16.800
[Guest]: pointless, because you might as well listen to the original then, right? Yeah, I don't

01:06:16.800 --> 01:06:19.320
[Guest]: want to hear somebody sounding like the Beatles if they're going to do that.

01:06:19.320 --> 01:06:23.400
[Guest]: Do you write original poetry? No, I don't. So I couldn't for the life of me, because

01:06:23.400 --> 01:06:28.200
[Amit Varma]: I've noticed that, you know, some of the translations from Indian languages of poetry in other languages

01:06:28.200 --> 01:06:33.000
[Unknown]: is by great poets themselves, like Arvind Krishna Mehrotra doing Kabir and Ranjit Hoskote

01:06:33.000 --> 01:06:38.240
[Amit Varma]: Lalde. And, you know, it almost seems to me that to be able to translate, you have to

01:06:38.240 --> 01:06:42.680
[Guest]: be a poet yourself. Yeah, except that I agree, except that I'm always worried about terms

01:06:42.680 --> 01:06:46.600
[Guest]: like am I a poet or am I not? Because you know, you may be a poet without having written

01:06:46.600 --> 01:06:49.760
[Guest]: a line of poetry for that matter. I mean, you may have all the qualities that a poet

01:06:49.760 --> 01:06:56.360
[Guest]: has. The thing is, poetry also eventually is a matter of appreciating the entire holistic

01:06:56.360 --> 01:07:01.760
[Guest]: effect of text, right? Including rhythm, including rhyme, including sound. So to that extent,

01:07:01.760 --> 01:07:06.600
[Guest]: poetry and prose are not that far apart. But it's just that because prose is more loosely,

01:07:06.600 --> 01:07:11.320
[Guest]: there's no structure in prose. I mean, just flowing sentence one after the other, whereas

01:07:11.320 --> 01:07:18.200
[Guest]: poetry has a line length, it has prosody, it has certain structured effects, as it were.

01:07:18.200 --> 01:07:23.320
[Guest]: So those are harder to put across. But very interestingly, Ranjit Hoskote's approach to

01:07:23.320 --> 01:07:27.400
[Guest]: translating is vastly different from Arvind Krishna Mehrotra's. I mean, Arvind Krishna

01:07:27.400 --> 01:07:33.640
[Guest]: Mehrotra rewrites poems. You know, he is actually, that's a true cover version. I mean, he brings

01:07:33.640 --> 01:07:38.880
[Guest]: Rastafarians into Kabir, which is great. It's wonderful to read. It's perhaps also only

01:07:38.880 --> 01:07:44.040
[Guest]: possible because there have been so many translations of Kabir. So now you can start reading these.

01:07:44.040 --> 01:07:48.840
[Guest]: If he were to be the first translator, then Kabir would have an entirely different...

01:07:48.840 --> 01:07:53.720
[Guest]: They'd all jump on Arvind Krishna Mehrotra also, like what are you doing? Exactly. Exactly.

01:07:53.720 --> 01:07:58.520
[Guest]: Whereas Ranjit Hoskote was doing Lal Dede, has to be... But Ranjit brings a different

01:07:58.520 --> 01:08:04.040
[Guest]: he is much more aware of the need to be, to put less of himself, maybe his skills, but

01:08:04.040 --> 01:08:07.600
[Guest]: not himself, not his sensibilities as a poet, if you know what I mean.

01:08:07.600 --> 01:08:11.800
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And the other question I have, and this also, I'll probably phrase it in a clumsy

01:08:11.800 --> 01:08:18.520
[Amit Varma]: way because I'm almost thinking aloud, is that a lot of us who are educated in English,

01:08:18.520 --> 01:08:23.680
[Amit Varma]: certainly me, we bring our biases to the table when we read anything. So I have a certain

01:08:23.680 --> 01:08:28.880
[Amit Varma]: way of looking at a text. For example, when I look at poetry, you know, I will value things

01:08:28.880 --> 01:08:34.160
[Amit Varma]: like economy. I'll value things like precision of language. You know, I'll value things like

01:08:34.160 --> 01:08:38.760
[Amit Varma]: what the specific rhythms that I'm used to thinking of as good poetry and so on and so

01:08:38.760 --> 01:08:42.520
[Amit Varma]: forth. Ditto with prose. You know, I might have my own specific taste, but there's a

01:08:42.520 --> 01:08:46.840
[Amit Varma]: certain sort of, even for people who haven't studied literature, just through the books

01:08:46.840 --> 01:08:51.520
[Amit Varma]: that are considered great, there's a certain pedagogy of values that this is what is good

01:08:51.520 --> 01:08:56.200
[Amit Varma]: and this is what is not. Now, the languages, as we discussed earlier, are so incredibly

01:08:56.200 --> 01:09:01.880
[Amit Varma]: different. You know, in Bengali, Tagore may write in very flowery, purple, vivid prose,

01:09:01.880 --> 01:09:06.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, a lot of subcontinental languages are certainly far more baroque than English.

01:09:06.960 --> 01:09:11.800
[Amit Varma]: And that's definitely not a value that you look for. You know, you want to cut out all

01:09:11.800 --> 01:09:15.960
[Amit Varma]: of that. If any word stands out, we are taught to cut it out. You don't want the language

01:09:15.960 --> 01:09:20.880
[Amit Varma]: to draw attention to itself per se. I mean, with exceptions such as, you know, magic realism

01:09:20.880 --> 01:09:25.040
[Amit Varma]: and whatever Rajshri does. And, you know, I'm not a huge fan of that, but that's a question

01:09:25.040 --> 01:09:30.960
[Amit Varma]: of taste. So is how we, and here I'm not talking about translation per se, but is how we look

01:09:30.960 --> 01:09:37.560
[Amit Varma]: at literature in languages other than English, colored by the values that we have imbibed

01:09:37.560 --> 01:09:42.120
[Amit Varma]: through studying or being exposed to English literature? I mean, is this a problem? And

01:09:42.120 --> 01:09:47.620
[Amit Varma]: is it, for example, something that you would face in practical terms that say you're translating

01:09:47.620 --> 01:09:52.720
[Amit Varma]: something from Bengali to English and is beautiful in the original and you're recreating its

01:09:52.720 --> 01:09:57.160
[Amit Varma]: essence in English. And therefore it is not precisely how a writer in English would write

01:09:57.160 --> 01:10:02.200
[Amit Varma]: it or consider good, but it still makes sense to you. How do you look at all of this?

01:10:02.200 --> 01:10:07.000
[Guest]: Yeah, no, I agree completely. And I think my personal aesthetic is also one toward one

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:13.160
[Guest]: that absorbs excessiveness, excesses of any kind. So it's a hard balance, but at the same

01:10:13.160 --> 01:10:18.720
[Guest]: time, you can't also completely strip the original text of its decorations or ornaments

01:10:18.720 --> 01:10:24.080
[Guest]: and so on. But it's just that the way I look at it is that what is this place of those

01:10:24.080 --> 01:10:29.000
[Guest]: decorations and embellishments in the original language. And sometimes when that becomes

01:10:29.000 --> 01:10:34.440
[Guest]: the norm, then its effect is actually much lower because it is not standing out. You're

01:10:34.440 --> 01:10:40.040
[Guest]: used to this sort of slightly exaggerated form, right? Everyone is, as I said, ghor

01:10:40.040 --> 01:10:44.320
[Guest]: kha kha kochcha always. No one will say ghor ta khali chilo, which is a more prosaic way

01:10:44.320 --> 01:10:48.880
[Guest]: of putting it. So when you encounter that all the time, you are actually all you're

01:10:48.880 --> 01:10:53.240
[Guest]: hearing is ghor ta khali chilo, nothing more than that. So it's fine then. You don't, there's

01:10:53.240 --> 01:10:58.320
[Guest]: no embellishment that you need to carry across. At other times, you see genuinely wonderful

01:10:58.320 --> 01:11:03.360
[Guest]: prose. Someone has really come up with something fantastic. And then you, then you sometimes

01:11:03.360 --> 01:11:08.040
[Guest]: you keep taking it into the new language and see, is it creating the same effect? Does

01:11:08.040 --> 01:11:13.240
[Guest]: it seem overblown or even under? Sometimes you may have not pitched it high enough. So

01:11:13.240 --> 01:11:21.280
[Guest]: you tweak. But you have to be sensitive to the natural tone of the language into which

01:11:21.280 --> 01:11:27.440
[Guest]: you're translating. And therefore, where a particular sentence stands with in relation

01:11:27.440 --> 01:11:32.040
[Guest]: to the natural tone of that language is where your translated sentence should stand in relation

01:11:32.040 --> 01:11:36.400
[Guest]: to the natural tone of that language. And the two natural tones may be quite different.

01:11:36.400 --> 01:11:40.560
[Guest]: Therefore, you will have to choose. But the relationship between the natural tone and

01:11:40.560 --> 01:11:45.160
[Guest]: that sentence should be the same, more or less. That's what I look at.

01:11:45.160 --> 01:11:49.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, I was struck by an example Rabasa gave of an exercise he carried out in his

01:11:49.920 --> 01:11:55.040
[Amit Varma]: class where and I don't remember the two languages involved. One of them was obviously English.

01:11:55.040 --> 01:11:59.000
[Amit Varma]: The other would have been Spanish, I guess. And he handed out a text to one student who

01:11:59.000 --> 01:12:03.720
[Amit Varma]: had to translate from Spanish to English. Next student had to translate that translation

01:12:03.720 --> 01:12:08.720
[Amit Varma]: back and so on all the way back to down the line. And then they would look at the final

01:12:08.720 --> 01:12:13.160
[Guest]: English version with the first English version and sort of compare. I've done that in my

01:12:13.160 --> 01:12:17.720
[Guest]: classes. You've done that in your class as well. So what have you found? So, you know,

01:12:17.720 --> 01:12:23.040
[Guest]: the divergence is less than I had thought. Oh, yeah. I thought it was like Chinese whispers.

01:12:23.040 --> 01:12:28.720
[Guest]: It would have been altered tremendously. Not quite so much. But you can see that it's not

01:12:28.720 --> 01:12:33.560
[Guest]: so much the writing that's different as the reading that's different. So two people have

01:12:33.560 --> 01:12:38.200
[Guest]: read the same word differently and therefore have written it in different ways or the same

01:12:38.200 --> 01:12:43.400
[Guest]: phrase differently. So really, the divergences come in the way in your reading. And in your

01:12:43.400 --> 01:12:48.840
[Guest]: reading comes your relationship with the language as well. You know, in fact, this is another

01:12:48.840 --> 01:12:54.400
[Guest]: very interesting point, which is that in the West, most people translate from a language

01:12:54.400 --> 01:13:03.200
[Guest]: that they have learnt into the language they live in, which is English. In our case, most

01:13:03.200 --> 01:13:07.600
[Guest]: of us translate from a language we live in. And English also we live in, in some senses

01:13:07.600 --> 01:13:12.400
[Guest]: in India, but perhaps the English we live in is not the English we translate into entirely.

01:13:12.400 --> 01:13:15.520
[Guest]: So because sometimes when you're translating into English, you're always thinking of an

01:13:15.520 --> 01:13:20.680
[Guest]: international audience as well. So because of this difference, we are perhaps better

01:13:20.680 --> 01:13:27.600
[Guest]: readers of the text than many Western translators are. But I guess they may be better writers.

01:13:27.600 --> 01:13:33.240
[Guest]: It's possible because they live their entire lives in English, right? We don't. Even despite

01:13:33.240 --> 01:13:37.640
[Guest]: our comfort and our familiarity with the English language, many parts of our lives are not

01:13:37.640 --> 01:13:42.600
[Guest]: lived in English at all. Whether it's your daily transactions, sometimes your thoughts,

01:13:42.600 --> 01:13:47.840
[Guest]: your most instinctive responses to something are often not in English, right? So we end

01:13:47.840 --> 01:13:52.720
[Guest]: up translating, I think, in a different way, which somehow I think is a little closer to

01:13:52.720 --> 01:13:57.960
[Guest]: the original text because we're reading it better and we're internalising it more. So

01:13:57.960 --> 01:14:04.040
[Guest]: the English that we reproduce it in will inevitably, I think, have more of the flavours of the

01:14:04.040 --> 01:14:08.640
[Guest]: original language, like it or not, than in the case of someone translating from say a

01:14:08.640 --> 01:14:12.160
[Guest]: French or a Spanish into. Of course, there's also the point that those languages are far

01:14:12.160 --> 01:14:18.000
[Guest]: more similar. Here, English comes from a completely different space. If you were translating from

01:14:18.000 --> 01:14:22.520
[Guest]: Hindi to Bengali, for example, it would not nearly be such a, as much of a leap.

01:14:22.520 --> 01:14:26.160
[Amit Varma]: No, and in fact that, you know, so there I'm thinking, for example, an American writer

01:14:26.160 --> 01:14:31.680
[Amit Varma]: who lives in Calcutta and learns Bengali will come up with a very different kind of translation

01:14:31.680 --> 01:14:37.000
[Amit Varma]: as someone like you would, who, you know, will find the sort of the familiar equivalent

01:14:37.000 --> 01:14:41.160
[Guest]: idiom in English much more. Yeah. And also, also perhaps have a better sense of what that

01:14:41.160 --> 01:14:45.920
[Guest]: where the text is, the original text is going beyond its dictionary meaning. And something

01:14:45.920 --> 01:14:49.640
[Amit Varma]: you said was interesting to me, which is, you know, when you said that we don't necessarily

01:14:49.640 --> 01:14:53.200
[Amit Varma]: translate in the same English we use, because it's also the question of an international

01:14:53.200 --> 01:14:57.240
[Amit Varma]: audience. Is that a consideration for you? Like when you translate, are you thinking

01:14:57.240 --> 01:15:01.800
[Amit Varma]: of audience or are you just thinking, okay, let me capture the joy that I feel?

01:15:01.800 --> 01:15:05.920
[Guest]: Primarily let me capture the joy that I feel, but when I'm validating that joy, I have to

01:15:05.920 --> 01:15:09.760
[Guest]: figure out whether it will register with the reader. And that point you start thinking,

01:15:09.760 --> 01:15:14.040
[Guest]: maybe not when the, when you're actually translating, but when you're reading, revising, you have

01:15:14.040 --> 01:15:18.360
[Guest]: to question your decisions to see someone who does not come armed with the same body

01:15:18.360 --> 01:15:22.720
[Guest]: of knowledge that you have, what it will mean to them is some, is a question you must.

01:15:22.720 --> 01:15:28.680
[Amit Varma]: So let's talk about your process now. Like, what is your process? Like when you get a

01:15:28.680 --> 01:15:33.680
[Amit Varma]: book, like first, I assume you will only translate books you enjoy reading is my guess. Or are

01:15:33.680 --> 01:15:34.680
[Guest]: you sometimes given a book?

01:15:34.680 --> 01:15:39.400
[Guest]: Sometimes I do get commissioned books, which are not necessarily books I would translate

01:15:39.400 --> 01:15:43.600
[Guest]: by choice. And I do it for various reasons, because increasingly I've discovered that

01:15:43.600 --> 01:15:50.040
[Guest]: this business of what I like is a little idiosyncratic, because as a translator, you also sort of

01:15:50.040 --> 01:15:55.320
[Guest]: have a responsibility towards the entire body of literature being produced in a language,

01:15:55.320 --> 01:16:00.360
[Guest]: or all its in all its variations and diversity. It is also important, increasingly, as we've

01:16:00.360 --> 01:16:03.560
[Guest]: learned that some voices need to be amplified.

01:16:03.560 --> 01:16:06.760
[Amit Varma]: Are you saying that because there aren't too many translators from Bengali to English allowed

01:16:06.760 --> 01:16:09.240
[Amit Varma]: and around, therefore, the responsibility is more on you?

01:16:09.240 --> 01:16:12.640
[Guest]: Well, no, no, no, I mean, there are more translators actually from Bengali to English than perhaps

01:16:12.640 --> 01:16:17.280
[Guest]: from any other language, to be honest. No, it's not more on me personally. But I'm just

01:16:17.280 --> 01:16:21.760
[Guest]: saying on all of us, on all of us, because the fact is that we are not as many as there

01:16:21.760 --> 01:16:26.680
[Guest]: are writers. So although it takes less time to perhaps translate than to write a book,

01:16:26.680 --> 01:16:31.920
[Guest]: but the thing is that you can't always go with only your personal taste 100%. That's

01:16:31.920 --> 01:16:36.560
[Guest]: all I'm saying. Because then important books, which you may not like, not all important

01:16:36.560 --> 01:16:40.680
[Guest]: books are books you may like, but they need to be translated for, let's say they come

01:16:40.680 --> 01:16:46.680
[Guest]: from an underrepresented voice, or they increasingly, for example, I've tried to make, I mean, over

01:16:46.680 --> 01:16:51.880
[Guest]: the past couple of years, I'm trying to get to a point where I say for every book I translate

01:16:51.880 --> 01:16:56.960
[Guest]: by a man, I will translate one by a woman also. So I want to ensure that 50% representation

01:16:56.960 --> 01:17:01.960
[Guest]: in my ongoing work. So sometimes, you know, when one picks up books that are important

01:17:01.960 --> 01:17:06.840
[Guest]: that you know need to be read, without it being a book that you personally would enjoy.

01:17:06.840 --> 01:17:11.280
[Amit Varma]: And does it expand you translating a book that you wouldn't otherwise have liked?

01:17:11.280 --> 01:17:17.440
[Guest]: Absolutely, absolutely. And sometimes what I do is, so this is interesting, very increasingly

01:17:17.440 --> 01:17:21.440
[Guest]: now I don't read the book through before translating it. Oh, yeah, I did a little bit and then

01:17:21.440 --> 01:17:26.840
[Guest]: I get into it. And I discovered the book as I'm going along. And while I can be cute and

01:17:26.840 --> 01:17:31.640
[Guest]: sort of say things like it reproduces the first reaction of the reader, when they're

01:17:31.640 --> 01:17:37.800
[Guest]: not familiar with the text and so on. The fact is that I enjoy it because I am actually

01:17:37.800 --> 01:17:41.760
[Amit Varma]: discovering the story as I'm going along. So you read enough to get the voice and then

01:17:41.760 --> 01:17:46.760
[Guest]: you just yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah. So starting with that is where I put the most effort really

01:17:46.760 --> 01:17:52.040
[Guest]: in doing the first few pages to make sure that I've got the voice. Once you feel you've

01:17:52.040 --> 01:17:57.440
[Guest]: got it, then I move very quickly. Because you always worried what if the voice leaves

01:17:57.440 --> 01:18:01.360
[Guest]: you at some point, or do you allow yourself to be distracted by other things, and then

01:18:01.360 --> 01:18:05.840
[Guest]: it's gone. That is, in fact, one of the toughest things because you also have to live at the

01:18:05.840 --> 01:18:09.880
[Guest]: same time, you're not just writing for people like us, we also have to do our day jobs,

01:18:09.880 --> 01:18:16.080
[Guest]: whatever they might be. So you have to inhabit the book very, very obsessively while you're

01:18:16.080 --> 01:18:19.560
[Guest]: translating it. I guess that's true of a writer as well, they have to inhabit whatever they're

01:18:19.560 --> 01:18:24.040
[Amit Varma]: writing. And is there and again, this is true of everyone, writers, translators, anybody

01:18:24.040 --> 01:18:29.800
[Amit Varma]: who does anything, is there a trade off between getting it right and getting it done? So do

01:18:29.800 --> 01:18:34.120
[Amit Varma]: you sort of like if you have a particularly problematic passage or a para or a bit of

01:18:34.120 --> 01:18:37.960
[Amit Varma]: dialogue and you're not sure what to do, do you just do it as best as you can literally

01:18:37.960 --> 01:18:41.440
[Guest]: and say, I'll come back to it later. Yes. And move on in the draft. Absolutely. I do

01:18:41.440 --> 01:18:45.640
[Guest]: not allow the flow to be impeded by anything. I mean, I very often leave entire chunks in

01:18:45.640 --> 01:18:49.440
[Guest]: the original without even translating because I know that that's going to engage a different

01:18:49.440 --> 01:18:55.120
[Guest]: part of my mind. And I don't want to suddenly change the rhythm of my writing at this point.

01:18:55.120 --> 01:19:00.600
[Guest]: So I do that. Yeah. Words, phrases, paragraphs. Sometimes I translate very literally knowing

01:19:00.600 --> 01:19:05.600
[Guest]: that I will come back to this, but the structure is so complex that I don't want to pause it

01:19:05.600 --> 01:19:09.440
[Guest]: right now. So in fact, that's one of the tricks we do in our translation class. And then when

01:19:09.440 --> 01:19:14.080
[Guest]: sentences prove very difficult to translate, we do an actual word by word rendition, which

01:19:14.080 --> 01:19:18.520
[Guest]: comes up quite beautifully as poetry almost. Because, you know, the syntax is mangled in

01:19:18.520 --> 01:19:21.680
[Guest]: English. Give me an example if you can think about it. So, you know, if you take a long

01:19:21.680 --> 01:19:29.280
[Guest]: sentence like a lullaby. Right. And you're trying, you're struggling with the rhythm

01:19:29.280 --> 01:19:33.280
[Guest]: of that in English and you're trying to compose it entirely in your head before you put it

01:19:33.280 --> 01:19:37.160
[Guest]: down and it's proving impossible. So then I tell the class, OK, let's just put down

01:19:37.160 --> 01:19:45.200
[Guest]: each word the way it is. So it's goom, sleep, parani, put, sleep, put, aunt. And as I go

01:19:45.200 --> 01:19:51.680
[Guest]: even more literal, mother, sister, father, sister, our house come. OK. And then they've

01:19:51.680 --> 01:19:56.080
[Guest]: suddenly got a skeleton. It's OK. Now let's play with this and see what interesting things

01:19:56.080 --> 01:20:00.280
[Guest]: we can do. Just like a hack to release the mind. Yeah, it's a hack to release the mind.

01:20:00.280 --> 01:20:03.760
[Guest]: Exactly. So that you know, because you're not struggling with structure and meaning

01:20:03.760 --> 01:20:09.040
[Guest]: at the same time. So you get the meaning out literally word for word. So now you know what

01:20:09.040 --> 01:20:13.320
[Guest]: words you have to capture. Now you find the right structure for it that will. So these

01:20:13.320 --> 01:20:17.400
[Guest]: things happen sometimes, you know, and they're quite interesting exercises. And they sometimes

01:20:17.400 --> 01:20:21.600
[Guest]: alert you to the richness of that original text. Because what we tend to do when we read

01:20:21.600 --> 01:20:26.240
[Guest]: is that we abstract the meaning and we tend to forget about other things. Right. So that's

01:20:26.240 --> 01:20:31.560
[Guest]: why one of the exercises I do with my class is I make them translate birdsong. Wow. So

01:20:31.560 --> 01:20:37.600
[Guest]: the whole idea behind birdsong is that there is no meaning. You have to translate sounds.

01:20:37.600 --> 01:20:43.280
[Guest]: And let your minds just put words to these sounds and then they create beautiful situations

01:20:43.280 --> 01:20:47.360
[Guest]: around those. What I also make them translate from languages they don't know and I don't

01:20:47.360 --> 01:20:52.560
[Guest]: know. Oh, okay. Yeah. So you know, almost none of us knows Norwegian or Swedish. So

01:20:52.560 --> 01:20:58.000
[Guest]: I take Swedish text and say translate. What the hell is this? I don't care. Just translate.

01:20:58.000 --> 01:21:02.320
[Guest]: Look at the text and do an English and then it opens, unlocks different parts of their

01:21:02.320 --> 01:21:10.800
[Guest]: mind where they try to, from sounds or from, okay, this is a short word, it may be a verb

01:21:10.800 --> 01:21:14.280
[Guest]: and so on. And they come up with something that is a quotient structure, which may not

01:21:14.280 --> 01:21:20.280
[Guest]: have any relationship in terms of significance with the original, but it alerts you to the

01:21:20.280 --> 01:21:27.040
[Guest]: fact that there is so much more to text than its bare dictionary meaning of each word.

01:21:27.040 --> 01:21:31.600
[Amit Varma]: So you know, now I'll completely digress and ask about teaching. Yeah. That, you know,

01:21:31.600 --> 01:21:36.040
[Amit Varma]: how do you learn this pedagogy? You know, what do I teach? How do I teach? You know,

01:21:36.040 --> 01:21:40.280
[Amit Varma]: you are basically before this, you are a doer. Yeah. You know, your strategy is internalized.

01:21:40.280 --> 01:21:44.400
[Unknown]: You are handling things tactically. Suddenly you have to teach a class and you've got all

01:21:44.400 --> 01:21:48.880
[Amit Varma]: these interesting methods. Yes. So number one, how do you devise these methods? And

01:21:48.880 --> 01:21:53.160
[Amit Varma]: number two, in this process, does it change the way you see your translation or do your

01:21:53.160 --> 01:21:58.120
[Guest]: translation? Yeah. Great, great question. So my first, and this is something that I've

01:21:58.120 --> 01:22:02.560
[Guest]: only managed to, I can articulate some of this now because I've thought about it. Again,

01:22:02.560 --> 01:22:07.080
[Guest]: I've gone, I'm an organic translator and I'm an organic teacher of translation. So my idea

01:22:07.080 --> 01:22:11.360
[Guest]: of teaching translation is let's translate. Let's not talk about it. And let's see what

01:22:11.360 --> 01:22:16.360
[Guest]: problems come up in the course of translation. So I still follow that. I just plunge people

01:22:16.360 --> 01:22:20.280
[Guest]: into it. And as I was telling you, I plunge people into it, not just in terms of meaning,

01:22:20.280 --> 01:22:26.000
[Guest]: but also both in terms of trying to capture all the richness of a text that exists outside

01:22:26.000 --> 01:22:31.320
[Guest]: of the dictionary meaning of the words and simultaneously also practice different forms

01:22:31.320 --> 01:22:35.400
[Guest]: of rendition. For example, one of the exercises I said to them is we'll do, let's do a feminist

01:22:35.400 --> 01:22:40.320
[Guest]: translation of a text where you're obviously allowed to play much more with the content,

01:22:40.320 --> 01:22:45.440
[Guest]: but you are true to a certain vision you have of the end product. So eventually you will

01:22:45.440 --> 01:22:50.400
[Guest]: marry the two where you will have a vision and you will have a sense of what the original

01:22:50.400 --> 01:22:57.000
[Guest]: text is. But first let's do them as separate exercises without being hamstrung by the need

01:22:57.000 --> 01:23:02.360
[Guest]: to do both at the same time. So, yeah, in fact, my classes, I do two or three things.

01:23:02.360 --> 01:23:08.360
[Guest]: For example, one of the things I do is I hand out a sheet, which is a combination of paragraphs

01:23:08.360 --> 01:23:13.040
[Guest]: of translated text and text written originally in English. And I ask them to identify which

01:23:13.040 --> 01:23:15.680
[Guest]: ones do you think are translations and which ones are not.

01:23:15.680 --> 01:23:17.520
[Guest]: And can they possibly do that?

01:23:17.520 --> 01:23:22.440
[Guest]: No, even I couldn't. The first time the exercise was given to me, I couldn't either. Then the

01:23:22.440 --> 01:23:26.960
[Guest]: point of the exercise is just that, that there is actually when you read the final thing,

01:23:26.960 --> 01:23:32.360
[Guest]: you're not, there's no difference, right? So let's not worry about some, you know, the

01:23:32.360 --> 01:23:36.360
[Guest]: anxieties of a translated text. A well translated text, no one will be able to tell apart from

01:23:36.360 --> 01:23:39.960
[Guest]: an original. So that's one exercise. Second exercise, as I mentioned, was things like

01:23:39.960 --> 01:23:45.560
[Guest]: birdsong and so on. The third exercise is that we translate, we translate pictures,

01:23:45.560 --> 01:23:50.320
[Guest]: you know, from movie scenes into scripts. So the whole idea is, can you see something

01:23:50.320 --> 01:23:54.800
[Guest]: visually and put words to it if the words are not there for you to begin with?

01:23:54.800 --> 01:23:56.320
[Guest]: Wow, that's so fascinating.

01:23:56.320 --> 01:24:01.920
[Guest]: Yeah. So then they do that. So that ultimately teaches them to read the text also for the

01:24:01.920 --> 01:24:06.480
[Guest]: visuals that are out there without only worrying about. Sometimes, you know, you lose the sight

01:24:06.480 --> 01:24:10.760
[Guest]: of the wood for the trees. And as a translator, you can't really do that. Rather you have

01:24:10.760 --> 01:24:15.200
[Guest]: to do both. You both have to go so down deep that you are looking only at the trees and

01:24:15.200 --> 01:24:21.120
[Guest]: even the wood. But then the entire wood must also, the forest must also be coming alive

01:24:21.120 --> 01:24:25.920
[Guest]: to you at the end of what you've done in the same way that it was there in the original.

01:24:25.920 --> 01:24:30.800
[Guest]: Other than that, my job is really to teach them to fall in love. How do you teach someone

01:24:30.800 --> 01:24:35.800
[Guest]: to fall in love? You can't, right? But you can create the conditions for them to fall

01:24:35.800 --> 01:24:36.800
[Amit Varma]: in love.

01:24:36.800 --> 01:24:40.280
[Amit Varma]: You recreate the joy, which it seems to me that you are doing because I am now tempted

01:24:40.280 --> 01:24:43.600
[Guest]: to just go and see a movie scene and try to do this. It's so exciting.

01:24:43.600 --> 01:24:46.880
[Guest]: So that's the thing. You recreate the conditions in which you will fall in love, right? You

01:24:46.880 --> 01:24:51.320
[Guest]: bring the chocolate and you bring the lovely person and you put them in the right frame

01:24:51.320 --> 01:24:56.720
[Guest]: of mind. But then you step back and say, OK, now if the magic has to happen, it will happen.

01:24:56.720 --> 01:25:01.160
[Guest]: These are the primary tasks of my teaching. Once that is done, then it boils down to,

01:25:01.160 --> 01:25:05.200
[Guest]: as we said, you know, specific questions that keep cropping up in the course of the text.

01:25:05.200 --> 01:25:09.420
[Guest]: And I teach translation without knowing the languages from which they're translating.

01:25:09.420 --> 01:25:13.080
[Guest]: And my point to them is that this is not a mathematics class. We are not testing for

01:25:13.080 --> 01:25:17.760
[Guest]: accuracy. That is, as a translator, that's your responsibility. No one can teach you

01:25:17.760 --> 01:25:23.480
[Guest]: how to do an accurate translation. I mean, in this day and age, it's not difficult at

01:25:23.480 --> 01:25:28.520
[Guest]: all. You will always get the meaning of every word. One of the translator's greatest tools

01:25:28.520 --> 01:25:33.480
[Guest]: today, by the way, and I'm very grateful for this, is Google Images.

01:25:33.480 --> 01:25:36.840
[Guest]: Because sometimes you don't know what the hell is this word, but then you put it into

01:25:36.840 --> 01:25:42.080
[Guest]: Google in the original language and you click on the images tab and you say, oh, that's

01:25:42.080 --> 01:25:47.520
[Guest]: what it is. I had no idea. And then you say, OK, now I figured out what it stands for.

01:25:47.520 --> 01:25:52.560
[Guest]: Yeah. So it's a huge, Google Images is a huge leap.

01:25:52.560 --> 01:25:58.560
[Amit Varma]: This is a fantastic hack. I just feel so excited. I'm learning so much. So how long does it

01:25:58.560 --> 01:26:03.200
[Amit Varma]: and how do you balance the sort of personal and it's not even the professional because

01:26:03.200 --> 01:26:08.280
[Amit Varma]: it's not your profession. How do you balance the regular rhythm of your life, which includes

01:26:08.280 --> 01:26:13.240
[Amit Varma]: everything else and the translation that you take on? And would it be different if translation

01:26:13.240 --> 01:26:14.240
[Amit Varma]: was your day job?

01:26:14.240 --> 01:26:19.000
[Guest]: Yeah. So it is my profession in the sense that it may not be my profession financially,

01:26:19.000 --> 01:26:22.080
[Guest]: but in every other sense, it's my profession. It's the one that I give.

01:26:22.080 --> 01:26:24.080
[Amit Varma]: It's a calling.

01:26:24.080 --> 01:26:30.040
[Guest]: It's my almost my identity now, primarily identity. Would it be different? Yes. I mean,

01:26:30.040 --> 01:26:36.800
[Guest]: I often fantasize about that, although I would not now not give up teaching for anything,

01:26:36.800 --> 01:26:42.160
[Guest]: but I still fantasize about a life of being only a literary translator. So in that life,

01:26:42.160 --> 01:26:47.640
[Guest]: I would be, so here's how my day would go. I would wake up in the morning and I would

01:26:47.640 --> 01:26:51.720
[Guest]: translate into Bangla first thing in the morning, which I do now. I've translated one book and

01:26:51.720 --> 01:26:55.480
[Guest]: I'm going to be doing more. So first thing in the morning for about two hours, when my

01:26:55.480 --> 01:27:02.000
[Guest]: mind is freshest after sleep, say from about six to eight, I would translate into Bangla.

01:27:02.000 --> 01:27:07.160
[Guest]: Then I would go for a walk, a long walk and have breakfast, then come back and then work

01:27:07.160 --> 01:27:13.440
[Guest]: on the main text that I'm translating for about four hours. So say till about one o'clock

01:27:13.440 --> 01:27:21.360
[Guest]: or so. Nap for 20 minutes, wake up and read. Read English.

01:27:21.360 --> 01:27:23.360
[Amit Varma]: What kind of Bengali naps for 20 minutes?

01:27:23.360 --> 01:27:29.120
[Guest]: No, I'm a bad Bengali in that sense. Yeah. So let's not call it a nap. I mean, let's

01:27:29.120 --> 01:27:30.520
[Amit Varma]: just, you know, shut my eyes.

01:27:30.520 --> 01:27:31.520
[Amit Varma]: Relax.

01:27:31.520 --> 01:27:37.840
[Guest]: I would read for a couple of hours, then translate again, but a different text. I would always

01:27:37.840 --> 01:27:43.120
[Guest]: be working on three texts. One into Bangla and one in the morning and one in the evening.

01:27:43.120 --> 01:27:48.840
[Guest]: And I'd knock off work by about eight o'clock or so and watch a film at night. That would

01:27:48.840 --> 01:27:49.840
[Amit Varma]: be my

01:27:49.840 --> 01:27:50.840
[Amit Varma]: That's your fantasy.

01:27:50.840 --> 01:27:53.120
[Guest]: Yeah, fantasy, no socialising, mind you. I mean, this is almost

01:27:53.120 --> 01:27:55.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's what I was wondering, why are you working till eight? I thought you'll work

01:27:55.320 --> 01:27:58.000
[Guest]: till five in the evening, you chill out with your friends and all that.

01:27:58.000 --> 01:28:02.400
[Guest]: I don't know. I mean, friends and all that happens anyway. I can't deal with meeting

01:28:02.400 --> 01:28:04.240
[Amit Varma]: people every day.

01:28:04.240 --> 01:28:07.160
[Guest]: All the more reason I'm so grateful that you've come here today.

01:28:07.160 --> 01:28:08.160
[Guest]: This is different.

01:28:08.160 --> 01:28:09.160
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:28:09.160 --> 01:28:10.840
[Amit Varma]: But you know, socially, I mean, every day is out of the question.

01:28:10.840 --> 01:28:14.640
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough. And so, you know, going back to the process, how long does it take you

01:28:14.640 --> 01:28:16.720
[Guest]: to translate a typical book?

01:28:16.720 --> 01:28:23.480
[Guest]: So depends on the length, of course, but my I aim to translate 3000 words a day in translation.

01:28:23.480 --> 01:28:28.640
[Guest]: So if it's a middle, medium sized book of about 60,000 words, it'll take me 20 days

01:28:28.640 --> 01:28:33.120
[Guest]: of 3000 words each, which eventually even inevitably becomes a month or so, because

01:28:33.120 --> 01:28:37.880
[Guest]: you don't achieve 3000 words every day. So yeah, it's I mean, I average, let's say, 50

01:28:37.880 --> 01:28:39.480
[Guest]: to 60,000 words a month.

01:28:39.480 --> 01:28:45.720
[Amit Varma]: Fantastic. And did you also sort of, like you mentioned that your first translation

01:28:45.720 --> 01:28:49.800
[Amit Varma]: when you were in college, when you were working rather at that magazine was one of Shankar's

01:28:49.800 --> 01:28:54.720
[Amit Varma]: stories, and he liked it, and he asked you to translate Chaurangi, which you did. So

01:28:54.720 --> 01:28:59.520
[Amit Varma]: do you have a lot of interaction with the writers themselves? What do they feel about

01:28:59.520 --> 01:29:00.520
[Unknown]: the work?

01:29:00.520 --> 01:29:05.800
[Guest]: Fortunately, no. Well, fortunately, and unfortunately, because I'm sure it would benefit I would,

01:29:05.800 --> 01:29:12.440
[Guest]: the work would benefit from these interactions. But see, here's the thing, most Bengali writers

01:29:12.440 --> 01:29:18.840
[Guest]: are not so able to read the English in a way that will tell them whether it's a good translator.

01:29:18.840 --> 01:29:22.680
[Guest]: I mean, they'll get a sense of it, but it won't go beyond that. Many of them are not

01:29:22.680 --> 01:29:30.520
[Guest]: interested. A third chunk are dead. So between them, I have had almost nobody look closely

01:29:30.520 --> 01:29:36.920
[Guest]: at a translation or so on. Once in a while, I've asked questions, but not too often.

01:29:36.920 --> 01:29:42.080
[Amit Varma]: And, and in the general, like one of the, you know, when I was reading interviews of

01:29:42.080 --> 01:29:48.960
[Amit Varma]: translators, a really common complaint is that is about the reviews, that either the

01:29:48.960 --> 01:29:53.520
[Amit Varma]: review won't even mention that it is a translation or talk about the translation, or in some

01:29:53.520 --> 01:29:58.360
[Amit Varma]: cases, a reviewer will say, well, I don't know the original language, so I cannot comment,

01:29:58.360 --> 01:30:03.720
[Amit Varma]: which according to Grossman, among others, is an inadequate response, because it's not

01:30:03.720 --> 01:30:07.640
[Amit Varma]: about precision of translation, it's about whatever you're creating. And translators

01:30:07.640 --> 01:30:13.960
[Amit Varma]: are often translators often feel that reviewers and many people in the general public as well,

01:30:13.960 --> 01:30:17.880
[Amit Varma]: don't really understand what they have done. They think that is like you're putting a bit

01:30:17.880 --> 01:30:21.980
[Amit Varma]: of tracing paper, say on a painting and you're kind of, but it's not that it's a it's an

01:30:21.980 --> 01:30:27.560
[Amit Varma]: act of recreation. And people don't often get this. Is that something you feel frustrated

01:30:27.560 --> 01:30:31.760
[Amit Varma]: by that? I mean, I know you won all these awards, and so on the crossword award for

01:30:31.760 --> 01:30:37.360
[Amit Varma]: translation twice, and so on. But is that something that sort of frustrates you that

01:30:37.360 --> 01:30:41.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, your translation doesn't get the kind of recognition it deserves? Perhaps you

01:30:41.040 --> 01:30:43.880
[Amit Varma]: don't get the kind of advances you deserve, so on and so forth?

01:30:43.880 --> 01:30:48.600
[Guest]: No, no, it doesn't frustrate me, doesn't frustrate me at all. Because I really see the translator

01:30:48.600 --> 01:30:54.760
[Guest]: as being a transparent individual. They do their job, but you know, the real, I mean,

01:30:54.760 --> 01:30:58.280
[Guest]: I'm happy if someone reads the book and says they liked it. That's, that's good enough

01:30:58.280 --> 01:31:01.800
[Guest]: for me, because then I know I've done a good job. And that's all that matters, whether

01:31:01.800 --> 01:31:05.320
[Guest]: they're saying you've done a good job, or the review says it or so on, is immaterial

01:31:05.320 --> 01:31:09.200
[Guest]: to me. And really, I think that too much, I mean, I know there are all the movements

01:31:09.200 --> 01:31:15.520
[Guest]: like Name the Translator, and so on, which are all good, and so on. But they distract,

01:31:15.520 --> 01:31:19.520
[Guest]: I think, in some ways, they're not crucial to the quality of translations, they're not

01:31:19.520 --> 01:31:24.200
[Guest]: crucial to ensuring that more translations are read, they're not crucial to ensuring

01:31:24.200 --> 01:31:29.000
[Guest]: the more translations are published, none of those, you know, feed into those important

01:31:29.000 --> 01:31:33.280
[Guest]: things. I think that's what the translator community should be fighting for. Certainly,

01:31:33.280 --> 01:31:38.960
[Guest]: the money would be useful. But again, how much money do writers make either? So to be

01:31:38.960 --> 01:31:43.640
[Guest]: honest, you can't complain. The trick for, if you live in India, the trick for you is

01:31:43.640 --> 01:31:47.600
[Guest]: actually to try to get published in the West as a translator. Because then the fees that

01:31:47.600 --> 01:31:53.000
[Guest]: you get are actually very handsome. Certainly, they're very handsome by Indian standards,

01:31:53.000 --> 01:31:57.920
[Guest]: but they're also pretty, I mean, I'll tell you brass tacks. It's very simple. In the

01:31:57.920 --> 01:32:07.600
[Guest]: UK, you get paid 90 pounds per 1000 words, per 100 words. So, no, 1000 words. So 50,000

01:32:07.600 --> 01:32:10.880
[Guest]: would give you, yeah, that's right, per 1000 words. So let's say if you were translating

01:32:10.880 --> 01:32:17.800
[Guest]: even a slim book of 50,000 words, you're talking about 4,500 pounds. 4,500 pounds is almost

01:32:17.800 --> 01:32:21.760
[Guest]: four and a half lakh rupees. In India, that goes a long way. You're certainly not going

01:32:21.760 --> 01:32:25.200
[Guest]: to get an advance of four and a half lakh rupees for a translation. I mean, the best

01:32:25.200 --> 01:32:30.320
[Guest]: advance you will get is maybe a lakh. And that too, if a publisher is trying to break

01:32:30.320 --> 01:32:33.560
[Guest]: into a market, when they're already settled, they will not pay that kind of advance.

01:32:33.560 --> 01:32:37.480
[Amit Varma]: So many young people are listening to this episode, excited by everything you have said

01:32:37.480 --> 01:32:40.840
[Guest]: so far, wanting to be translators, and you've just brought them crashing down.

01:32:40.840 --> 01:32:46.080
[Guest]: Yeah, well, if you, if you, I mean, my point is that I don't think you can actually be

01:32:46.080 --> 01:32:47.640
[Amit Varma]: a great artist if you're given the money.

01:32:47.640 --> 01:32:49.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but you have to do it for the love of it.

01:32:49.240 --> 01:32:53.480
[Guest]: Yeah, it's not going to happen. And almost conversely, if you, the more you do it for

01:32:53.480 --> 01:32:58.440
[Guest]: the love of it, the more money you will make. And the more happy you will be because you're

01:32:58.440 --> 01:33:03.200
[Guest]: not expecting anything to begin with. But it is also, I think, you know, we also have

01:33:03.200 --> 01:33:08.480
[Guest]: locked ourselves into a kind of consumer lifestyle, which perhaps if you're really serious about

01:33:08.480 --> 01:33:12.760
[Guest]: being a translator, and today's generation is actually quite different in that sense.

01:33:12.760 --> 01:33:18.080
[Guest]: They're far more, they want to live far more lightly. So it could be possible. I wouldn't

01:33:18.080 --> 01:33:24.040
[Guest]: make it. In fact, I know, an Italian, translated into Italian, Joya, I'll just call her Joya,

01:33:24.040 --> 01:33:28.840
[Guest]: strangely Indian sounding name. She's used to spend half a year in India, because it

01:33:28.840 --> 01:33:31.960
[Guest]: was cheaper to live in India, given what she was earning.

01:33:31.960 --> 01:33:37.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I've met her. Yeah, yeah, yeah. Fine lady. Yeah. Yeah. So, you know, given everything

01:33:37.720 --> 01:33:41.120
[Amit Varma]: you just said about not being social and all of that, and you have translation to get back

01:33:41.120 --> 01:33:45.120
[Amit Varma]: to, I'm very grateful you gave me so much time, I won't take much more of it. Final

01:33:45.120 --> 01:33:49.280
[Amit Varma]: question, something that listeners of my show often ask me for, and I think the part of

01:33:49.280 --> 01:33:54.560
[Amit Varma]: the show that they enjoy the most is when my guest is recommending books for them to

01:33:54.560 --> 01:34:00.440
[Amit Varma]: read. And in this case is particularly pertinent, because it's your whole life. So a dual question,

01:34:00.440 --> 01:34:06.080
[Amit Varma]: really. One is that out of those who are translated, whom you've translated and even otherwise,

01:34:06.080 --> 01:34:10.520
[Amit Varma]: who are the writers you really, really love who means something to you. And apart from

01:34:10.520 --> 01:34:15.200
[Amit Varma]: that, if you had to sort of recommend three works that you have translated that you're

01:34:15.200 --> 01:34:19.600
[Amit Varma]: particularly proud of, not just as translations, but you feel they are great books, you feel

01:34:19.600 --> 01:34:22.640
[Amit Varma]: everyone should read this, you know, what would they be?

01:34:22.640 --> 01:34:26.680
[Guest]: Okay, so as for the writers, are you talking about writers only who write in Bangla?

01:34:26.680 --> 01:34:30.920
[Amit Varma]: Let's stay with Bangla, because other guests will recommend other people.

01:34:30.920 --> 01:34:38.880
[Guest]: Sure. Yeah. So in Bangla, I think the people to really read are Mahasheta Devi, for sure.

01:34:38.880 --> 01:34:45.040
[Guest]: And the brilliant thing about Mahasheta Devi is that her work will remain alive. I'm not

01:34:45.040 --> 01:34:49.160
[Guest]: going to use a word like relevant, because that is too narrow. Her work will remain alive

01:34:49.160 --> 01:34:56.200
[Guest]: for many generations to come. So Mahasheta Devi, her son, Naubarun Bhattacharya, whose

01:34:56.200 --> 01:35:02.440
[Guest]: writing has this manic energy, which you would not think literature capable of actually holding,

01:35:02.440 --> 01:35:03.440
[Guest]: leave alone conveying.

01:35:03.440 --> 01:35:07.720
[Amit Varma]: Was he particularly hard to translate? Or was he energising?

01:35:07.720 --> 01:35:12.120
[Guest]: He was tremendously energising. And in fact, there's been a newer translation of that book

01:35:12.120 --> 01:35:18.920
[Guest]: by Shunandini Mukherjee at Seagull, and hers is even better. It's not even, it's actually

01:35:18.920 --> 01:35:24.320
[Guest]: better than mine, because I think she's taken off where I left off, as it were. So, you

01:35:24.320 --> 01:35:29.040
[Guest]: know, she's gone out more on a limbo over there to reproduce that energy and that sense

01:35:29.040 --> 01:35:33.800
[Guest]: of manic adventure that this text contains. So these two, for sure, I would recommend

01:35:33.800 --> 01:35:41.200
[Guest]: Asha Punnadevi, because she has this incredible ability to locate her stories within these

01:35:41.200 --> 01:35:48.160
[Guest]: four walls, and home in on the aspects of human beings, which we tend not to look at,

01:35:48.160 --> 01:35:52.160
[Guest]: because we all tend to think of human beings as being very noble people, right? We're noble

01:35:52.160 --> 01:35:57.200
[Guest]: and we're always striving to be better versions of ourselves and so on. And she just goes

01:35:57.200 --> 01:36:05.280
[Guest]: in at the pettiness and the weaknesses and the foibles and the way they create discord

01:36:05.280 --> 01:36:10.760
[Guest]: in the tightness and the claustrophobic kind of spaces that middle class families live

01:36:10.760 --> 01:36:16.640
[Guest]: in. It's fascinating. And she's able to do, I mean, she has written over, what, I think

01:36:16.640 --> 01:36:21.080
[Guest]: two or 3000 stories. Great literature for me takes me to, this is something Nadeem Aslam

01:36:21.080 --> 01:36:25.520
[Guest]: said, and I completely love what he said. He said, it takes you to a place where you've

01:36:25.520 --> 01:36:29.280
[Guest]: never been before. And when you go there, you feel I've lived here all my life.

01:36:29.280 --> 01:36:30.280
[Guest]: Wow.

01:36:30.280 --> 01:36:35.440
[Guest]: Yeah. So that's exactly what she does. It's fantastic. So her, definitely. Let's see who

01:36:35.440 --> 01:36:42.160
[Guest]: are the others. There are writers like Shruthi Nath Bhaduri, who used to live in, you know,

01:36:42.160 --> 01:36:46.920
[Guest]: many of the Bengali writers who wrote in the first half of the 20th century, actually lived

01:36:46.920 --> 01:36:51.120
[Guest]: and grew up in what is Bihar now. So Shruthi Nath Bhaduri was one of them. Shruthi Nath

01:36:51.120 --> 01:36:55.800
[Guest]: Bhaduri has this fantastic book called Doraichorit Manosh, which is, as you can make out from

01:36:55.800 --> 01:37:00.160
[Guest]: the name, a take off on the Ramcharitmanas, and Dora is the name of the place. It's an

01:37:00.160 --> 01:37:05.680
[Guest]: extraordinary book. And it's been translated, fortunately. So him, Shundipan Chattopadhyay,

01:37:05.680 --> 01:37:12.000
[Guest]: who was one of those plotless writers, who arrived at this fantastic vignettes of human

01:37:12.000 --> 01:37:15.960
[Guest]: behaviour, and always with the sense that you were looking at something deeper than

01:37:15.960 --> 01:37:21.480
[Guest]: you thought. And in the most, amidst squalor, amidst middle class meanness, middle class

01:37:21.480 --> 01:37:28.260
[Guest]: poverty and so on, and yet very strongly informed by human desire, which is somewhat unusual

01:37:28.260 --> 01:37:32.040
[Guest]: for Indian literatures, you know, where the human desire doesn't play a very big part.

01:37:32.040 --> 01:37:39.080
[Guest]: And desire in a very cheap, tawdry way, not even particularly poetic or anything. Very

01:37:39.080 --> 01:37:44.800
[Guest]: real, therefore. Anita Agnihotri, who writes from her own experiences as a bureaucrat,

01:37:44.800 --> 01:37:48.160
[Guest]: although she writes in Bangla, her fiction is said all over India.

01:37:48.160 --> 01:37:51.720
[Guest]: I think you got the 2011 Crossword Award for translating her work.

01:37:51.720 --> 01:37:56.880
[Guest]: So her works are quite amazing, and especially because they take you out of your known spaces,

01:37:56.880 --> 01:38:05.880
[Guest]: and they actually sensitize you to politics, to social fault lines, to poverty, to living

01:38:05.880 --> 01:38:10.720
[Guest]: conditions and so on. Always looks at those stories through what human beings are doing.

01:38:10.720 --> 01:38:15.160
[Guest]: I mean, they're not bland treatises, he's not throwing data at you, or anything like

01:38:15.160 --> 01:38:22.840
[Guest]: that. So these people for sure. And I would actually say Tagore's short stories, they

01:38:22.840 --> 01:38:23.840
[Guest]: really are something.

01:38:23.840 --> 01:38:27.560
[Amit Varma]: I mean, some of them are already part of the popular culture in such a way that it almost

01:38:27.560 --> 01:38:28.560
[Guest]: seems cliched like Abliwala.

01:38:28.560 --> 01:38:32.840
[Guest]: Yeah, exactly. But there are a whole bunch of others which are, you can, there's so much

01:38:32.840 --> 01:38:38.000
[Guest]: you can get out of if you wanted to do a feminist reading of Tagore's stories, for example,

01:38:38.000 --> 01:38:42.240
[Guest]: but written by, so was he an ally? The question is, forget about whether he was a feminist,

01:38:42.240 --> 01:38:47.400
[Guest]: was he an ally? Here's this very upper middle class, very privileged person. Was he an ally

01:38:47.400 --> 01:38:52.240
[Guest]: or was it sort of pretense of understanding? So there are very many important critical

01:38:52.240 --> 01:38:56.520
[Guest]: questions you can throw at his stories, and you will always come back. And you don't necessarily

01:38:56.520 --> 01:39:00.880
[Guest]: have to say, the answer is not always yes. But the point is, he's engaging, he's engaging

01:39:00.880 --> 01:39:05.280
[Guest]: with all these things. And even if his viewpoint is not one you agree with, you are grateful

01:39:05.280 --> 01:39:09.200
[Guest]: that he's engaging with it and he's raising the question back in that day, back in that

01:39:09.200 --> 01:39:14.560
[Guest]: day in and framing them in a way that the questions remain relevant now, whatever your

01:39:14.560 --> 01:39:20.080
[Guest]: answers may be. He framed them in a tremendously modern or, I would say, out of time, you know,

01:39:20.080 --> 01:39:26.160
[Guest]: in a way that does not, cannot be pinned down to a particular time or social system or anything.

01:39:26.160 --> 01:39:30.960
[Guest]: In Bangladesh, there are these great writers. And in fact, that I can segue into the next

01:39:30.960 --> 01:39:34.640
[Guest]: question for that. I've finished the translation, which is going to be published later this

01:39:34.640 --> 01:39:40.520
[Guest]: year of Akhtaruz Zaman Ilyas's Khwab Nama, which to me is the most mind-blowing novel

01:39:40.520 --> 01:39:41.520
[Guest]: I've ever read.

01:39:41.520 --> 01:39:42.520
[Guest]: Tell me a bit about it.

01:39:42.520 --> 01:39:47.680
[Guest]: Khwab Nama is set in just before and just after independence and partition. It's set

01:39:47.680 --> 01:39:53.560
[Guest]: in a village cluster in the north of what is now Bangladesh. It is set in the background

01:39:53.560 --> 01:39:58.960
[Guest]: of the Tehbaga movement. So it's a confluence of many streams. You have the Tehbaga movement

01:39:58.960 --> 01:40:04.080
[Guest]: going on where farmers are agitating for their rights to the land. They want it to be Tehbaga

01:40:04.080 --> 01:40:10.880
[Guest]: three parts and they want two thirds of the takings. You have the whole independence or

01:40:10.880 --> 01:40:16.240
[Guest]: rather the partition track. So you have, therefore, the Hindu-Muslim track. You have oppression.

01:40:16.240 --> 01:40:22.320
[Guest]: You have personal desire. You have magical realism, because things are happening that

01:40:22.320 --> 01:40:27.960
[Guest]: cannot quite be explained. You have hunger in a very big way. Food and hunger is such

01:40:27.960 --> 01:40:32.360
[Guest]: an important part of that book. And there is this one character who doesn't have a name.

01:40:32.360 --> 01:40:37.600
[Guest]: He's called Tameez's father, Tameez-e-Baap. And Tameez-e-Baap is perpetually hungry and

01:40:37.600 --> 01:40:43.040
[Guest]: he can put away enormous quantities of food and he becomes a mythical figure eventually.

01:40:43.040 --> 01:40:51.080
[Guest]: And it is written in, you know, it's written in a way that is, you almost feel like, no,

01:40:51.080 --> 01:40:56.960
[Guest]: how can a person have so many perspectives in the same novel? And it is not conscious.

01:40:56.960 --> 01:41:01.640
[Guest]: It's not that he's telling the story through X's eye or Y's eye or Z's eye or anything,

01:41:01.640 --> 01:41:09.000
[Guest]: but he just, he seamlessly, you know, shifts his, the camera seamlessly shifts his position.

01:41:09.000 --> 01:41:15.320
[Guest]: And it's an extraordinary work. So both in literary terms and in terms of being a document

01:41:15.320 --> 01:41:20.080
[Guest]: of, so Akhtaruzaman L.A.S. wrote just two novels in his life. He wrote this one and

01:41:20.080 --> 01:41:25.440
[Guest]: his second novel, his first novel was called Chile Kota Shepai, The Soldier in the Attic.

01:41:25.440 --> 01:41:29.120
[Guest]: And he developed cancer while he was writing his second novel, and he died soon after finishing

01:41:29.120 --> 01:41:33.360
[Guest]: it. It's almost like he willed himself to finish the novel before he died. And he wrote

01:41:33.360 --> 01:41:34.360
[Guest]: a bunch of short stories.

01:41:34.360 --> 01:41:35.760
[Amit Varma]: Have you translated that one also?

01:41:35.760 --> 01:41:41.520
[Guest]: No, but I may. I mean, there is another translator from Bangladesh who's very keen, but he says

01:41:41.520 --> 01:41:44.240
[Guest]: he doesn't have the time. And if it turns out that he doesn't have the time, then I'm

01:41:44.240 --> 01:41:45.800
[Amit Varma]: going to do it. Otherwise, he will do it.

01:41:45.800 --> 01:41:49.760
[Guest]: Any other translations of yours you'd like to recommend? What are your sentimental favourites?

01:41:49.760 --> 01:41:55.120
[Guest]: Well, sentimental favourite would be Buddhadeb Bose's When the Time is Right. It's just an

01:41:55.120 --> 01:41:59.320
[Guest]: extraordinary piece of writing. It's not so much the story or anything, it's an extraordinary

01:41:59.320 --> 01:42:04.840
[Guest]: piece of writing, but it is a very real, it's set in, again, just before independence, it's

01:42:04.840 --> 01:42:10.680
[Guest]: set at a time when the old order of the Bengali aristocracy is crumbling, and there's lots

01:42:10.680 --> 01:42:17.640
[Guest]: of money because of the war, and a newer bunch of Bengalis are rising. And yet they are associated

01:42:17.640 --> 01:42:23.720
[Guest]: by the aristocracy with being crude, and money is after all vulgar, and so on. So there's

01:42:23.720 --> 01:42:28.000
[Guest]: this very interesting clash between these two worldviews, but told beautifully through

01:42:28.000 --> 01:42:32.840
[Guest]: the story of one family, one family with a gentleman whose wife dies after giving birth

01:42:32.840 --> 01:42:37.240
[Guest]: to their fifth daughter. So there are five sisters in this story, but only one of them

01:42:37.240 --> 01:42:41.680
[Guest]: is pivotal, the youngest one. It's a love story as well. But I'm most interested in

01:42:41.680 --> 01:42:47.080
[Guest]: the third part of the novel, which is almost half of the novel, which is a description

01:42:47.080 --> 01:42:53.640
[Guest]: of one night, not even one night of four or five hours of a wedding. And it's this grand

01:42:53.640 --> 01:42:58.040
[Guest]: wedding that is taking place under the specter of the Japanese about to bomb Calcutta or

01:42:58.040 --> 01:43:03.320
[Guest]: fears that they might bomb Calcutta. And it's almost the last fling of the old aristocracy

01:43:03.320 --> 01:43:09.500
[Guest]: before they know that they will be eclipsed. And the writing is like a camera moving in

01:43:09.500 --> 01:43:15.880
[Guest]: and out of rooms. And it moves between, I mean, you know, it goes up to two people who

01:43:15.880 --> 01:43:19.800
[Guest]: are having a conversation. Halfway through a sentence, I don't want to hear anymore.

01:43:19.800 --> 01:43:24.680
[Guest]: It moves on and catches the second half of a sentence somebody else is uttering somewhere.

01:43:24.680 --> 01:43:29.600
[Guest]: And so in this way, it's sort of, you know, restlessly circulating around the whole space

01:43:29.600 --> 01:43:35.840
[Guest]: and making you see and listen to what's going on. So it's like a plotless film, almost in

01:43:35.840 --> 01:43:36.840
[Guest]: words, quite remarkable.

01:43:36.840 --> 01:43:39.600
[Amit Varma]: Wow, I can't wait to read all these books.

01:43:39.600 --> 01:43:41.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I will make sure I get these books across to you.

01:43:41.760 --> 01:43:45.280
[Amit Varma]: No, no, I'm going to pick them up. Please don't get them across to me. Let the royalties

01:43:45.280 --> 01:43:49.520
[Amit Varma]: go where they should. You know, thank you so much. This has been such an enriching discussion

01:43:49.520 --> 01:43:50.520
[Guest]: for me. Thanks so much for your time.

01:43:50.520 --> 01:43:54.920
[Guest]: Thank you, Amit. I mean, I don't think I've had a better chat on translating ever.

01:43:54.920 --> 01:43:57.600
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

